WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.475 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.475 --> 00:00:03.960 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:07.425 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.425 --> 00:00:11.700 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:13.840 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So I
decided to teach 18.156

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:17.080 align:middle line:84%
this semester about something
called projection theory.

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:20.280 align:middle line:84%
I think that projection theory,
although it's not usually

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:22.220 align:middle line:84%
highlighted in
graduate real analysis,

00:00:22.220 --> 00:00:25.280 align:middle line:84%
is a fairly fundamental
thing in analysis,

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:27.800 align:middle line:84%
a little bit like the
isoperimetric inequality

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:30.580 align:middle line:84%
or the Sobolev inequality, maybe
not quite that fundamental,

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:33.680 align:middle line:84%
but a fairly basic
thing that comes up

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:36.440 align:middle line:90%
in a lot of different places.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:39.160 align:middle line:84%
And I was excited to teach
about it this semester

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:41.720 align:middle line:90%
for a few reasons.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:47.020 align:middle line:84%
So one is that some of
the core basic questions--

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:49.560 align:middle line:84%
one of the core basic
questions in projection theory

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:51.740 align:middle line:84%
was just figured out in
the last couple of years.

00:00:51.740 --> 00:00:54.600 align:middle line:84%
And it's something that I'm
excited about learning about.

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:56.000 align:middle line:90%
So I wanted to--

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.300 align:middle line:84%
so that was one reason I was
excited to teach about it.

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:00.540 align:middle line:84%
And the other reason is
that I have gradually

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:04.060 align:middle line:84%
seen it appearing in more
and more different places.

00:01:04.060 --> 00:01:07.020 align:middle line:84%
And so I wanted to
highlight the way

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:09.400 align:middle line:84%
it comes up in a bunch of
different parts of math.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:12.620 align:middle line:90%


00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:15.020 align:middle line:84%
So today in the first class,
I'm going to tell you--

00:01:15.020 --> 00:01:17.160 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to do an overview
of projection theory.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:21.020 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to tell you what it
is, what the questions are,

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:23.825 align:middle line:84%
and about some of the different
applications, and maybe

00:01:23.825 --> 00:01:25.700 align:middle line:84%
a little bit about some
of the different ways

00:01:25.700 --> 00:01:27.040 align:middle line:90%
we think about it.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:37.740 align:middle line:90%


00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:40.380 align:middle line:84%
I guess it's a little
crowded in the back.

00:01:40.380 --> 00:01:42.080 align:middle line:84%
Are we-- I guess
the seats are full.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:43.320 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to start slowly.

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:46.560 align:middle line:84%
So if you want to grab a
chair or anything, feel free.

00:01:46.560 --> 00:02:04.930 align:middle line:90%


00:02:04.930 --> 00:02:10.449 align:middle line:84%
So the setup is that we are
in Rd, or maybe also a vector

00:02:10.449 --> 00:02:12.370 align:middle line:90%
space over another field later.

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:14.610 align:middle line:84%
And then we have
orthogonal projections.

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:17.680 align:middle line:90%
So V in Rd is a subspace.

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.650 align:middle line:90%


00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:24.230 align:middle line:84%
And pi sub v is the
orthogonal projection.

00:02:24.230 --> 00:02:32.783 align:middle line:90%


00:02:32.783 --> 00:02:34.450 align:middle line:84%
So what we're going
to do is we're going

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:37.570 align:middle line:90%
to consider some set, x in Rd.

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:40.610 align:middle line:84%
And then you can take
the orthogonal projection

00:02:40.610 --> 00:02:46.770 align:middle line:84%
of x in many different
directions for many different v.

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:51.970 align:middle line:84%
And we'll study how
that all fits together.

00:02:51.970 --> 00:03:00.750 align:middle line:84%
Study x and this guy
for many different V.

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:03.350 align:middle line:84%
So a slightly corny metaphor
for what we're doing

00:03:03.350 --> 00:03:05.450 align:middle line:90%
is we're studying some set.

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:09.230 align:middle line:84%
And you can look at the set
from many different directions.

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:13.670 align:middle line:84%
And we want to put
together the information

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:17.258 align:middle line:84%
from these different
points of view.

00:03:17.258 --> 00:03:18.300 align:middle line:90%
So let me make a picture.

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:27.110 align:middle line:90%


00:03:27.110 --> 00:03:29.110 align:middle line:90%
Red.

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:32.790 align:middle line:84%
So we'll come back to
this picture a bunch.

00:03:32.790 --> 00:03:35.400 align:middle line:90%
So maybe x is a set of red dots.

00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:42.630 align:middle line:90%


00:03:42.630 --> 00:03:45.590 align:middle line:84%
And then we can take the
projection of this set x

00:03:45.590 --> 00:03:48.750 align:middle line:90%
onto different planes.

00:03:48.750 --> 00:03:51.510 align:middle line:90%
So if I draw sort of a--

00:03:51.510 --> 00:03:54.050 align:middle line:90%
I'll draw one plane over here.

00:03:54.050 --> 00:04:08.580 align:middle line:84%
And if I project x onto this
plane, then I will get this.

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:12.210 align:middle line:90%


00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:17.410 align:middle line:90%
So there is pi v1 x.

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:20.010 align:middle line:84%
But I have rigged this--
so if I project it

00:04:20.010 --> 00:04:23.210 align:middle line:84%
onto a different plane,
something a bit interesting

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:23.720 align:middle line:90%
will happen.

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:33.530 align:middle line:90%


00:04:33.530 --> 00:04:36.690 align:middle line:90%
Here is a different plane, v2.

00:04:36.690 --> 00:04:41.890 align:middle line:84%
And if I project my set
onto v2, all of those points

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:43.880 align:middle line:84%
will kind of line up
on top of each other.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:46.410 align:middle line:90%


00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:48.730 align:middle line:84%
And all of those
points will kind of

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:50.160 align:middle line:90%
line up on top of each other.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:53.280 align:middle line:90%


00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:57.260 align:middle line:84%
And all of these points kind of
line up on top of each other.

00:04:57.260 --> 00:05:06.680 align:middle line:90%


00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:09.740 align:middle line:84%
Here are my observations
about this situation.

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:13.600 align:middle line:90%


00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:17.240 align:middle line:90%
So x itself is 8 dots.

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:22.960 align:middle line:84%
And when I projected x onto
v1, it was still 8 dots.

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:29.080 align:middle line:84%
But when I projected it onto
v2, there were only 3 dots,

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:32.680 align:middle line:84%
because there were a lot of
coincidences where dots got

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:33.980 align:middle line:90%
pushed on top of each other.

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:37.075 align:middle line:90%


00:05:37.075 --> 00:05:43.520 align:middle line:84%
Now, intuitively, v2 is kind of
special, and v1 is more typical.

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:46.100 align:middle line:84%
So most of the v's
will be like v1.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:48.265 align:middle line:84%
But there'll be a
few exceptional ones

00:05:48.265 --> 00:05:48.973 align:middle line:90%
that are like v2.

00:05:48.973 --> 00:05:53.060 align:middle line:90%


00:05:53.060 --> 00:06:03.180 align:middle line:84%
So intuition is that a v2
type situation is rare.

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:07.460 align:middle line:84%
And one of our goals is
to make that precise.

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:10.820 align:middle line:84%
Make a precise question,
and say precisely how

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:11.910 align:middle line:90%
rare is that behavior.

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:25.020 align:middle line:90%


00:06:25.020 --> 00:06:29.660 align:middle line:84%
So informally, if the set
x is kind of spread out,

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:33.260 align:middle line:84%
most of its projections will
also be kind of spread out.

00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:36.140 align:middle line:84%
There could be a few projections
where x gets kind of squished

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:37.340 align:middle line:90%
together.

00:06:37.340 --> 00:06:39.420 align:middle line:84%
And a projection
estimate means we'll

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:43.760 align:middle line:84%
try to quantify how often that
happens and show that it's rare.

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:47.360 align:middle line:90%


00:06:47.360 --> 00:06:52.160 align:middle line:84%
So we will make this precise
in a bunch of different ways.

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:56.760 align:middle line:84%
And I think the most simple to
ask question is when the set

00:06:56.760 --> 00:06:58.100 align:middle line:90%
x is a finite set.

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:02.080 align:middle line:90%


00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:08.240 align:middle line:84%
So now let's suppose
that x is a finite set.

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:13.880 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to use a notation
that absolute value of x

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:15.980 align:middle line:90%
is the cardinality of x.

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:26.120 align:middle line:90%


00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:27.720 align:middle line:90%
So here's my setup.

00:07:27.720 --> 00:07:32.400 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to take x in R2.

00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:39.440 align:middle line:84%
And E sub s of x is
going to be the set of v.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:41.980 align:middle line:84%
Let me actually-- let me mention
another piece of notation.

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:45.120 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to talk about
all these different subspaces v.

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:48.000 align:middle line:84%
So there's a name for the
family of all subspaces.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.460 align:middle line:90%
It's called the Grassmannian.

00:07:50.460 --> 00:07:53.380 align:middle line:84%
So another piece of
Grassmannian notation

00:07:53.380 --> 00:07:58.300 align:middle line:84%
is that the Grassmannian
of k planes in Rd.

00:07:58.300 --> 00:08:03.580 align:middle line:84%
This is the set
of v and Rd, where

00:08:03.580 --> 00:08:06.470 align:middle line:90%
v is a k-dimensional subspace.

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:10.940 align:middle line:90%


00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:16.220 align:middle line:84%
So E sub s of x is the
set of v. These are going

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:22.460 align:middle line:84%
to be one-dimensional subspaces
in R2 with the property

00:08:22.460 --> 00:08:28.160 align:middle line:84%
that the cardinality of
pi v of x is at most s.

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:32.299 align:middle line:90%


00:08:32.299 --> 00:08:35.940 align:middle line:84%
So going back to our basic
picture, if these red dots were

00:08:35.940 --> 00:08:40.780 align:middle line:84%
just points, then
this v2 would be

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:44.500 align:middle line:84%
in E sub 3 of x, because
pi v2 is only 3 points.

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:50.850 align:middle line:90%


00:08:50.850 --> 00:08:53.910 align:middle line:84%
So the first
question, if you like,

00:08:53.910 --> 00:08:58.490 align:middle line:84%
of projection theory
would be estimate

00:08:58.490 --> 00:09:00.250 align:middle line:84%
how many of these
directions there

00:09:00.250 --> 00:09:09.030 align:middle line:84%
are the size of Es of x in
terms of s and the size of x.

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:26.520 align:middle line:90%


00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:29.350 align:middle line:84%
So what would be an
interesting set x to consider?

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:32.970 align:middle line:84%
What would be a set x
of points or red dots

00:09:32.970 --> 00:09:35.090 align:middle line:84%
that in many
different directions

00:09:35.090 --> 00:09:36.710 align:middle line:90%
things would get squished a lot?

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:41.163 align:middle line:90%


00:09:41.163 --> 00:09:42.330 align:middle line:90%
Do people have any thoughts?

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:46.202 align:middle line:84%
What would be an
interesting x to look at?

00:09:46.202 --> 00:09:46.910 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: A grid.

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:49.530 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: A grid, yeah.

00:09:49.530 --> 00:09:52.060 align:middle line:84%
So as an example, let's
look at a square grid.

00:09:52.060 --> 00:10:05.110 align:middle line:90%


00:10:05.110 --> 00:10:07.510 align:middle line:84%
So x is going to
be the set of pairs

00:10:07.510 --> 00:10:11.470 align:middle line:84%
a, b, where a and
b are integers,

00:10:11.470 --> 00:10:13.290 align:middle line:90%
and they go from 1 up to n.

00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:24.590 align:middle line:90%


00:10:24.590 --> 00:10:25.510 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:27.630 align:middle line:84%
So this set has
small projections

00:10:27.630 --> 00:10:29.562 align:middle line:84%
in a bunch of
different directions.

00:10:29.562 --> 00:10:31.020 align:middle line:84%
Let me make it a
little bit bigger.

00:10:31.020 --> 00:10:40.170 align:middle line:90%


00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:45.170 align:middle line:84%
So x has n squared points,
16 points in my picture.

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:48.210 align:middle line:84%
If I project it down,
I only get 4 points.

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:50.680 align:middle line:84%
If I project it to the
side, I only get 4 points.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:53.610 align:middle line:90%


00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:59.220 align:middle line:84%
If I project it at 45 degrees,
I also get rather few points.

00:10:59.220 --> 00:11:02.090 align:middle line:90%


00:11:02.090 --> 00:11:03.950 align:middle line:90%
I project it at 45 degrees.

00:11:03.950 --> 00:11:07.890 align:middle line:84%
The fibers of the projection
will look like this.

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:11.690 align:middle line:84%
And they'll each have many
points, and so the projection

00:11:11.690 --> 00:11:13.150 align:middle line:90%
itself will be pretty small.

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:16.730 align:middle line:90%


00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:20.850 align:middle line:84%
Are there other angles as
well where I could project it

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:23.010 align:middle line:90%
and it would be pretty small?

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:26.290 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Some rational angles?

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:28.160 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah,
some rational angles.

00:11:28.160 --> 00:11:31.370 align:middle line:90%


00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:46.360 align:middle line:84%
So if we project x at a
rational angle, then pi v of x

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:48.560 align:middle line:90%
would be small.

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:55.000 align:middle line:84%
I'll draw one more, which I
think is enough to get the idea.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:56.800 align:middle line:84%
I remember when
I first saw it, I

00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:59.320 align:middle line:84%
could see the 45 degrees,
and the vertical,

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:01.160 align:middle line:90%
and the horizontal.

00:12:01.160 --> 00:12:07.760 align:middle line:84%
So if I project it perpendicular
to these orange lines, where

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:18.120 align:middle line:84%
it has a slope like left 1
and up 2, all of those fibers

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:19.340 align:middle line:90%
will also be large.

00:12:19.340 --> 00:12:21.090 align:middle line:84%
And so that projection
will also be small.

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:28.360 align:middle line:90%


00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:28.940 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:12:28.940 --> 00:12:31.540 align:middle line:84%
So we will compute it tomorrow
in the overview class.

00:12:31.540 --> 00:12:33.660 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to do
computations with you.

00:12:33.660 --> 00:12:36.780 align:middle line:84%
But if you do that, you will
find the following thing,

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:43.020 align:middle line:84%
that Es of x is around s
squared over the size of x

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:47.420 align:middle line:90%
for a big range of values of s.

00:12:47.420 --> 00:12:52.160 align:middle line:84%
So in between x to the
1/2 and, say, 1/2 of x.

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:56.708 align:middle line:90%


00:12:56.708 --> 00:12:58.500 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: That's
specifically for the grid?

00:12:58.500 --> 00:12:59.917 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH:
Yeah, for the grid.

00:12:59.917 --> 00:13:06.740 align:middle line:90%


00:13:06.740 --> 00:13:10.540 align:middle line:84%
Erdos did basically this
computation in the 1960s.

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:13.980 align:middle line:84%
And he made a conjecture that
the grid is the shape that

00:13:13.980 --> 00:13:15.333 align:middle line:90%
makes these the biggest.

00:13:15.333 --> 00:13:17.000 align:middle line:84%
These had a slightly
different language,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:18.860 align:middle line:84%
but his conjecture
implied that the grid

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:22.980 align:middle line:84%
is the configuration that
makes these sets the largest.

00:13:22.980 --> 00:13:24.320 align:middle line:90%
And that turned out to be true.

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:27.270 align:middle line:84%
And it was proven in the early
'80s by Szemerédi and Trotter.

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:35.760 align:middle line:90%


00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:45.040 align:middle line:84%
So they proved that if x is in
R2 and s is at most size of x/2,

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:53.480 align:middle line:84%
then the size of Es
of x is at most 1

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:56.470 align:middle line:84%
plus a constant times
what you see for the grid.

00:13:56.470 --> 00:14:11.860 align:middle line:90%


00:14:11.860 --> 00:14:13.360 align:middle line:84%
So this can be
considered, in a way,

00:14:13.360 --> 00:14:17.560 align:middle line:84%
one of the fundamental
theorems of projection theory.

00:14:17.560 --> 00:14:19.760 align:middle line:84%
And I'll mention a
couple interesting things

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:22.600 align:middle line:90%
about the proof.

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:25.680 align:middle line:84%
So one thing is the background
of these people, Erdos,

00:14:25.680 --> 00:14:28.040 align:middle line:84%
Szemerédi, and Trotter,
these are people

00:14:28.040 --> 00:14:29.540 align:middle line:90%
who come from combinatorics.

00:14:29.540 --> 00:14:32.550 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem represents a
connection between combinatorics

00:14:32.550 --> 00:14:33.970 align:middle line:90%
and projection theory.

00:14:33.970 --> 00:14:37.630 align:middle line:84%
And we'll talk about some
other aspects as we go along.

00:14:37.630 --> 00:14:43.130 align:middle line:84%
However, this proof is
not, at least at the time,

00:14:43.130 --> 00:14:45.345 align:middle line:84%
was not a traditional
combinatorial proof.

00:14:45.345 --> 00:14:47.970 align:middle line:84%
So they first played around with
a lot of combinatorial things,

00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:49.512 align:middle line:84%
double counting and
things like that,

00:14:49.512 --> 00:14:51.190 align:middle line:90%
and they couldn't prove it.

00:14:51.190 --> 00:14:54.470 align:middle line:84%
And then the proof eventually
uses in a crucial way

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:56.510 align:middle line:90%
the topology of R2.

00:14:56.510 --> 00:15:00.550 align:middle line:84%
So it's an interesting
connection between topology

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:03.150 align:middle line:90%
and this stuff.

00:15:03.150 --> 00:15:06.130 align:middle line:84%
So I'll just put here,
proof based on topology.

00:15:06.130 --> 00:15:14.038 align:middle line:90%


00:15:14.038 --> 00:15:17.370 align:middle line:84%
So this story is one important
story in projection theory.

00:15:17.370 --> 00:15:20.150 align:middle line:84%
But it's a very discrete
story about finite sets.

00:15:20.150 --> 00:15:23.030 align:middle line:84%
And there's another more
continuous, more analytic story,

00:15:23.030 --> 00:15:25.510 align:middle line:84%
which will be important
in our class, where

00:15:25.510 --> 00:15:27.870 align:middle line:84%
instead of taking a finite
set and projecting it,

00:15:27.870 --> 00:15:30.370 align:middle line:84%
we take a function, which you
can think of as like a density

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:32.410 align:middle line:90%
function.

00:15:32.410 --> 00:15:33.910 align:middle line:84%
Before I transition
there, actually,

00:15:33.910 --> 00:15:35.390 align:middle line:90%
let me pause here and see.

00:15:35.390 --> 00:15:37.510 align:middle line:84%
Are there any questions
or comments so far?

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:40.850 align:middle line:90%


00:15:40.850 --> 00:15:41.850 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:15:41.850 --> 00:15:44.690 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So for the
theorem that the grid kind

00:15:44.690 --> 00:15:51.050 align:middle line:84%
of the maximizes Es of x, is
that kind of the only example?

00:15:51.050 --> 00:15:53.850 align:middle line:84%
Or is there a kind of big
class of other examples

00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:55.990 align:middle line:90%
that also reach that bound?

00:15:55.990 --> 00:15:56.990 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK, cool.

00:15:56.990 --> 00:16:00.570 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, is the
grid the only example that's

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:01.950 align:middle line:90%
kind of tight for this theorem?

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:04.090 align:middle line:84%
Or are there lots
of other examples?

00:16:04.090 --> 00:16:06.130 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so another--
actually, a third thing

00:16:06.130 --> 00:16:08.330 align:middle line:84%
I like about projection
theory is that it's

00:16:08.330 --> 00:16:10.010 align:middle line:90%
full of open questions.

00:16:10.010 --> 00:16:12.450 align:middle line:84%
So it is a long-standing
open question

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:14.730 align:middle line:84%
whether the grid is
basically the only example

00:16:14.730 --> 00:16:18.010 align:middle line:84%
or whether there
are lots of others.

00:16:18.010 --> 00:16:22.750 align:middle line:84%
In terms of other examples that
we know about, there are a few,

00:16:22.750 --> 00:16:25.130 align:middle line:84%
but I would describe them
all as very minor variations

00:16:25.130 --> 00:16:25.950 align:middle line:90%
on the grid.

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:28.488 align:middle line:84%
And we can meet
them as we go along.

00:16:28.488 --> 00:16:30.530 align:middle line:84%
But in terms of a theorem
in the other direction,

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:32.070 align:middle line:90%
we know very little.

00:16:32.070 --> 00:16:34.950 align:middle line:84%
So it may or may not be the
case that there are many more

00:16:34.950 --> 00:16:36.050 align:middle line:90%
examples out there.

00:16:36.050 --> 00:16:38.670 align:middle line:90%


00:16:38.670 --> 00:16:40.230 align:middle line:90%
Nice.

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:41.210 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:16:41.210 --> 00:16:47.870 align:middle line:90%


00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:50.570 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:16:50.570 --> 00:16:54.390 align:middle line:84%
So now, let me describe a much
more analytic framework that

00:16:54.390 --> 00:16:55.730 align:middle line:90%
also involves projections.

00:16:55.730 --> 00:16:58.070 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see that
it's sort of related--

00:16:58.070 --> 00:16:59.370 align:middle line:90%
that it's related to this.

00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:20.190 align:middle line:90%


00:17:20.190 --> 00:17:23.589 align:middle line:84%
Now, instead of having a set,
suppose I have a function on R

00:17:23.589 --> 00:17:27.700 align:middle line:90%
to the d, say a complex value.

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:33.100 align:middle line:84%
And I'd like you to visualize
this as a density function.

00:17:33.100 --> 00:17:36.260 align:middle line:84%
So actually, a good thing
to picture is a CAT scan.

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:39.820 align:middle line:84%
So inside of your
body, there's something

00:17:39.820 --> 00:17:43.240 align:middle line:84%
that they'd like to scan, where
are the bones or something.

00:17:43.240 --> 00:17:49.580 align:middle line:84%
And so there's some
density of that thing.

00:17:49.580 --> 00:17:52.260 align:middle line:84%
And then the CAT
scan will shoot rays

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:54.820 align:middle line:84%
through your bodies in
different directions.

00:17:54.820 --> 00:18:00.740 align:middle line:84%
And it will compute the integral
of that function along the ray.

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:05.000 align:middle line:84%
And so if you stand
in front of a screen,

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.500 align:middle line:90%
maybe you just have an X-ray.

00:18:06.500 --> 00:18:07.720 align:middle line:90%
X-rays go through.

00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:10.780 align:middle line:84%
And what you see on the
screen is the amount of stuff

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:13.780 align:middle line:90%
that that X-ray went through.

00:18:13.780 --> 00:18:16.110 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we'd like
to do with this function.

00:18:16.110 --> 00:18:19.060 align:middle line:90%


00:18:19.060 --> 00:18:25.780 align:middle line:84%
So suppose here is our subspace
v. And if I have a point in it,

00:18:25.780 --> 00:18:29.680 align:middle line:84%
y, then the
orthogonal projection

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:32.320 align:middle line:90%
maps this fiber onto y.

00:18:32.320 --> 00:18:37.320 align:middle line:84%
So that there is
pi v inverse of y.

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:40.110 align:middle line:84%
So pi v inverse of y will
be an affine subspace.

00:18:40.110 --> 00:18:44.000 align:middle line:90%


00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:50.080 align:middle line:84%
And it has a volume
measure, which

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:54.600 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to call d
volume sub F. The letter F

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:55.782 align:middle line:90%
stands for fiber.

00:18:55.782 --> 00:18:58.240 align:middle line:84%
It's just to distinguish it
from d volume, which might mean

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:02.000 align:middle line:90%
the volume on the whole space.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:07.880 align:middle line:84%
So then the way I will define
the projection of the function

00:19:07.880 --> 00:19:11.720 align:middle line:84%
of y is I will
integrate over the fiber

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:16.230 align:middle line:90%
f of x d volume of the fiber.

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:19.080 align:middle line:90%


00:19:19.080 --> 00:19:23.540 align:middle line:84%
So another way to think about
this projection of the function

00:19:23.540 --> 00:19:29.980 align:middle line:84%
is that if I were to integrate
the projection of f on some set

00:19:29.980 --> 00:19:36.500 align:middle line:84%
u in the fiber,
so maybe over here

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:40.608 align:middle line:90%
I have some set u in my fiber.

00:19:40.608 --> 00:19:41.650 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] dy?

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:45.020 align:middle line:90%


00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:47.632 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, it's
d volume of the fiber of y.

00:19:47.632 --> 00:19:49.090 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, this thing
you could call dy.

00:19:49.090 --> 00:19:56.860 align:middle line:90%


00:19:56.860 --> 00:19:57.560 align:middle line:90%
Is that OK?

00:19:57.560 --> 00:20:00.260 align:middle line:90%


00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:06.620 align:middle line:84%
Then this would be equal to the
integral over the preimage of u

00:20:06.620 --> 00:20:08.360 align:middle line:90%
of f of x dx.

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:13.100 align:middle line:90%


00:20:13.100 --> 00:20:14.617 align:middle line:90%
D-- oh, I'm sorry.

00:20:14.617 --> 00:20:15.200 align:middle line:90%
You are right.

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:17.380 align:middle line:84%
Yes, that should not be
d volume of the fiber.

00:20:17.380 --> 00:20:19.020 align:middle line:90%
Thanks there.

00:20:19.020 --> 00:20:21.760 align:middle line:90%
So yeah, this is just dy.

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:23.920 align:middle line:84%
Or if you wanted to put
d volume of something,

00:20:23.920 --> 00:20:27.543 align:middle line:84%
it should be d volume
in the space v of y,

00:20:27.543 --> 00:20:28.460 align:middle line:90%
but not in the factor.

00:20:28.460 --> 00:20:29.140 align:middle line:90%
That's absolutely right.

00:20:29.140 --> 00:20:30.265 align:middle line:90%
What I wrote made no sense.

00:20:30.265 --> 00:20:36.520 align:middle line:90%


00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:39.680 align:middle line:84%
So if you integrate
the projection

00:20:39.680 --> 00:20:41.620 align:middle line:90%
of f over this region u.

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:44.070 align:middle line:84%
That's the integral of f
over the whole preimage.

00:20:44.070 --> 00:20:53.120 align:middle line:90%


00:20:53.120 --> 00:20:56.830 align:middle line:84%
Do you feel like you have
an image of what this means?

00:20:56.830 --> 00:21:01.285 align:middle line:90%


00:21:01.285 --> 00:21:02.660 align:middle line:84%
So now we can play
the same game.

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:03.713 align:middle line:90%
We start with a function.

00:21:03.713 --> 00:21:05.880 align:middle line:84%
And then you can consider
many different projections

00:21:05.880 --> 00:21:08.360 align:middle line:90%
of this function.

00:21:08.360 --> 00:21:13.360 align:middle line:84%
And there's a phenomenon, which
is similar to this phenomenon,

00:21:13.360 --> 00:21:16.640 align:middle line:84%
but the way it plays out in
this setting of functions

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:20.510 align:middle line:84%
is that most of the
projections are smoother

00:21:20.510 --> 00:21:22.590 align:middle line:90%
than the original function.

00:21:22.590 --> 00:21:24.850 align:middle line:84%
And I'll illustrate
that with a proposition.

00:21:24.850 --> 00:21:29.470 align:middle line:90%


00:21:29.470 --> 00:21:41.150 align:middle line:84%
So proposition, if f is
just an L2 function in R7,

00:21:41.150 --> 00:21:49.150 align:middle line:84%
then for almost every v, which
is a one-dimensional subspace

00:21:49.150 --> 00:21:56.510 align:middle line:84%
in R7, if you look at the
projection of f onto v,

00:21:56.510 --> 00:21:57.780 align:middle line:90%
it is a C2 function.

00:21:57.780 --> 00:22:04.470 align:middle line:90%


00:22:04.470 --> 00:22:07.010 align:middle line:90%
So this function on R7 is an L2.

00:22:07.010 --> 00:22:08.760 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't have to be
continuous anywhere.

00:22:08.760 --> 00:22:11.870 align:middle line:84%
It certainly doesn't have
to be differentiable.

00:22:11.870 --> 00:22:16.110 align:middle line:84%
You project it onto various
one-dimensional subspaces.

00:22:16.110 --> 00:22:17.250 align:middle line:90%
Now, not every one.

00:22:17.250 --> 00:22:17.750 align:middle line:90%
There are.

00:22:17.750 --> 00:22:19.330 align:middle line:84%
There are some bad
ones, where it's

00:22:19.330 --> 00:22:22.530 align:middle line:90%
only L2, or maybe even worse.

00:22:22.530 --> 00:22:27.080 align:middle line:84%
But for most of them,
the projection is C2.

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:28.830 align:middle line:84%
And if you play around
with these numbers,

00:22:28.830 --> 00:22:31.122 align:middle line:84%
if you make this bigger, you
can make it even smoother.

00:22:31.122 --> 00:22:33.710 align:middle line:90%


00:22:33.710 --> 00:22:35.530 align:middle line:90%
So I want to try to-- yeah.

00:22:35.530 --> 00:22:38.410 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What's special about
R7 here that makes this true?

00:22:38.410 --> 00:22:40.710 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: 7 is
not that special.

00:22:40.710 --> 00:22:43.500 align:middle line:84%
But increasing this
number makes it smoother.

00:22:43.500 --> 00:22:46.010 align:middle line:90%


00:22:46.010 --> 00:22:48.190 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there are similar
theorems in any dimension.

00:22:48.190 --> 00:22:57.690 align:middle line:90%


00:22:57.690 --> 00:23:01.410 align:middle line:84%
So let me try to give some
intuition about why that is

00:23:01.410 --> 00:23:06.490 align:middle line:84%
and to try to convince you
that that is a closely related

00:23:06.490 --> 00:23:09.530 align:middle line:84%
phenomenon to the phenomenon
that we started with that

00:23:09.530 --> 00:23:12.850 align:middle line:84%
appears in the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem.

00:23:12.850 --> 00:23:15.930 align:middle line:84%
So what's the
intuition about this?

00:23:15.930 --> 00:23:18.210 align:middle line:84%
So I have this high
dimensional function,

00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:20.150 align:middle line:90%
which is quite irregular.

00:23:20.150 --> 00:23:22.050 align:middle line:84%
And because it's
quite irregular,

00:23:22.050 --> 00:23:24.170 align:middle line:84%
you could picture it having
many peaks and valleys

00:23:24.170 --> 00:23:26.710 align:middle line:90%
and being very jagged.

00:23:26.710 --> 00:23:30.310 align:middle line:84%
But then when you integrate
it over the fibers,

00:23:30.310 --> 00:23:33.750 align:middle line:84%
if you integrate both
a peak and a valley,

00:23:33.750 --> 00:23:35.590 align:middle line:90%
they cancel each other out.

00:23:35.590 --> 00:23:38.570 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of those peaks and
valleys cancel each other out.

00:23:38.570 --> 00:23:43.130 align:middle line:84%
And you could hope to be
left with something smoother.

00:23:43.130 --> 00:23:47.033 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to make a picture.

00:23:47.033 --> 00:23:47.950 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to pick--

00:23:47.950 --> 00:23:49.070 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to erase
this, but I'm going

00:23:49.070 --> 00:23:50.362 align:middle line:90%
to draw a very similar picture.

00:23:50.362 --> 00:23:59.230 align:middle line:90%


00:23:59.230 --> 00:24:02.750 align:middle line:84%
So in my picture, my
f is going to have--

00:24:02.750 --> 00:24:10.150 align:middle line:84%
it's going to have
peaks on the red dots,

00:24:10.150 --> 00:24:11.245 align:middle line:90%
just to help me visualize.

00:24:11.245 --> 00:24:13.120 align:middle line:84%
So this function doesn't
exactly have values.

00:24:13.120 --> 00:24:14.640 align:middle line:84%
It's a picture of
flat landscape,

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:17.900 align:middle line:90%
but with lots of little peaks.

00:24:17.900 --> 00:24:22.270 align:middle line:84%
And so here are some red dots to
make them a little bit fatter.

00:24:22.270 --> 00:24:29.740 align:middle line:90%


00:24:29.740 --> 00:24:32.000 align:middle line:84%
So I think I'm not going to
try to draw the function,

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.080 align:middle line:84%
but what I want
you to visualize is

00:24:34.080 --> 00:24:35.580 align:middle line:84%
there's the plane
of the blackboard,

00:24:35.580 --> 00:24:40.180 align:middle line:84%
and then there's a peak coming
out over each of these things.

00:24:40.180 --> 00:24:44.980 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's try to
visualize what happens

00:24:44.980 --> 00:24:48.580 align:middle line:90%
when I project onto this space.

00:24:48.580 --> 00:24:55.420 align:middle line:84%
And in yellow, I'm going to
draw the function pi v of f.

00:24:55.420 --> 00:24:59.480 align:middle line:84%
So to help myself draw, I'll
put some little guidelines.

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:02.300 align:middle line:90%


00:25:02.300 --> 00:25:07.820 align:middle line:84%
So out here, pi v of f is just
0, because there were no peaks.

00:25:07.820 --> 00:25:11.600 align:middle line:84%
And then it's going to
go up as I see this peak.

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:14.260 align:middle line:84%
And then as I get here,
there are two peaks.

00:25:14.260 --> 00:25:15.920 align:middle line:90%
So that's even taller.

00:25:15.920 --> 00:25:19.600 align:middle line:84%
And then here, a little
shorter, here a little taller,

00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:21.232 align:middle line:90%
a little shorter.

00:25:21.232 --> 00:25:22.900 align:middle line:90%
It looks something like that.

00:25:22.900 --> 00:25:26.080 align:middle line:90%


00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:28.600 align:middle line:84%
You might notice already
that this is not as

00:25:28.600 --> 00:25:31.160 align:middle line:90%
jagged as the original thing.

00:25:31.160 --> 00:25:32.920 align:middle line:84%
Actually, probably,
it would be better

00:25:32.920 --> 00:25:34.230 align:middle line:90%
if I did something like this.

00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:39.480 align:middle line:90%


00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:41.780 align:middle line:84%
And because it's
the law of averages,

00:25:41.780 --> 00:25:44.840 align:middle line:84%
if I stick these around, or if
I stick them around randomly,

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:46.340 align:middle line:84%
then because of the
law of averages,

00:25:46.340 --> 00:25:48.760 align:middle line:90%
this will be pretty steady.

00:25:48.760 --> 00:25:50.740 align:middle line:84%
And even if I don't
pick them randomly,

00:25:50.740 --> 00:25:52.880 align:middle line:84%
if I choose v randomly,
there's a certain amount

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:54.100 align:middle line:90%
of the law of averages.

00:25:54.100 --> 00:25:56.110 align:middle line:84%
And this is going to
look relatively steady.

00:25:56.110 --> 00:26:01.120 align:middle line:90%


00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:02.280 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:05.160 align:middle line:84%
So qualitatively, this
is kind of similar

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:07.280 align:middle line:84%
to the Szemerédi-Trotter
theorem.

00:26:07.280 --> 00:26:13.120 align:middle line:84%
It says that there are
only a few bad directions.

00:26:13.120 --> 00:26:15.080 align:middle line:84%
And except for those
bad directions,

00:26:15.080 --> 00:26:19.540 align:middle line:84%
when I project this
down, I will see

00:26:19.540 --> 00:26:21.280 align:middle line:90%
things kind of averaging out.

00:26:21.280 --> 00:26:26.340 align:middle line:90%


00:26:26.340 --> 00:26:30.212 align:middle line:84%
And this proposition is
one way to make it precise,

00:26:30.212 --> 00:26:32.420 align:middle line:84%
but actually, we'll spend
some time thinking together

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:34.670 align:middle line:84%
about various ways
to make this precise.

00:26:34.670 --> 00:26:40.973 align:middle line:90%


00:26:40.973 --> 00:26:41.890 align:middle line:90%
Questions or comments?

00:26:41.890 --> 00:26:46.620 align:middle line:90%


00:26:46.620 --> 00:26:48.180 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:26:48.180 --> 00:26:49.900 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is it
possible sometimes

00:26:49.900 --> 00:26:52.460 align:middle line:84%
to prove the discrete
statements like this based

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:56.542 align:middle line:90%
on the continuous versions?

00:26:56.542 --> 00:26:58.000 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH:
Yeah, good question.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:01.540 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, can
we go back and forth

00:27:01.540 --> 00:27:02.920 align:middle line:90%
between these two worlds?

00:27:02.920 --> 00:27:05.420 align:middle line:84%
Can we take, say, the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem

00:27:05.420 --> 00:27:08.130 align:middle line:84%
or something like that and use
it to prove some continuous

00:27:08.130 --> 00:27:09.330 align:middle line:90%
estimates?

00:27:09.330 --> 00:27:12.050 align:middle line:84%
Or vice versa, can we take
some continuous estimates

00:27:12.050 --> 00:27:13.910 align:middle line:84%
and use it to prove
things like this?

00:27:13.910 --> 00:27:18.270 align:middle line:90%


00:27:18.270 --> 00:27:21.330 align:middle line:84%
So both of those things
are sometimes possible.

00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:24.410 align:middle line:84%
But both of those things
have some difficulties.

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:29.170 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, there's a big
story in the field in the class

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:34.050 align:middle line:84%
that people spent a lot of
energy trying to translate this

00:27:34.050 --> 00:27:35.500 align:middle line:90%
into the continuous setting.

00:27:35.500 --> 00:27:38.650 align:middle line:90%


00:27:38.650 --> 00:27:43.310 align:middle line:84%
And the original
proof doesn't work.

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:45.030 align:middle line:90%
And we had to think a lot.

00:27:45.030 --> 00:27:48.390 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we'll come back to that
a little later in the class.

00:27:48.390 --> 00:27:52.010 align:middle line:84%
But there's a story I want to
share with you about how it's

00:27:52.010 --> 00:27:54.730 align:middle line:84%
difficult to get from
this discrete setting

00:27:54.730 --> 00:27:56.120 align:middle line:90%
to the continuous set.

00:27:56.120 --> 00:28:09.865 align:middle line:90%


00:28:09.865 --> 00:28:11.490 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me say
a little bit more.

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:15.110 align:middle line:84%
So this example is
really pretty typical.

00:28:15.110 --> 00:28:18.270 align:middle line:84%
So you can suppose that your
function is a sum of bumps

00:28:18.270 --> 00:28:19.910 align:middle line:90%
on different little balls.

00:28:19.910 --> 00:28:21.830 align:middle line:84%
And so it is just a
question about how

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:25.670 align:middle line:84%
these different balls, small
balls are projecting down.

00:28:25.670 --> 00:28:27.990 align:middle line:84%
And it sounds, at first,
very similar to have

00:28:27.990 --> 00:28:30.430 align:middle line:84%
a bunch of delta balls
and project them down

00:28:30.430 --> 00:28:34.070 align:middle line:84%
to have a bunch of points
and project them down.

00:28:34.070 --> 00:28:36.970 align:middle line:84%
But the thickness of the
balls is really important.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:42.510 align:middle line:90%


00:28:42.510 --> 00:28:46.490 align:middle line:84%
It makes things different in
ways that we'll talk about.

00:28:46.490 --> 00:28:46.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:28:46.990 --> 00:28:47.370 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:48.990 align:middle line:84%
Would you mind saying
a bit more about--

00:28:48.990 --> 00:28:50.490 align:middle line:84%
so if I understand
correctly, you're

00:28:50.490 --> 00:28:52.770 align:middle line:84%
saying in the typical case
of a continuous setting,

00:28:52.770 --> 00:28:53.955 align:middle line:90%
you have some [INAUDIBLE]?

00:28:53.955 --> 00:28:55.830 align:middle line:84%
In the typical case, in
the discrete setting,

00:28:55.830 --> 00:28:58.270 align:middle line:90%
you recover all the points.

00:28:58.270 --> 00:29:00.157 align:middle line:84%
Could you say a bit
more about [INAUDIBLE]?

00:29:00.157 --> 00:29:00.990 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:29:00.990 --> 00:29:02.250 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:29:02.250 --> 00:29:03.550 align:middle line:90%
So the question is--

00:29:03.550 --> 00:29:06.750 align:middle line:84%
so the observation is that
in the discrete setting,

00:29:06.750 --> 00:29:11.130 align:middle line:84%
we had a theorem that says for
most directions of projections,

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:14.570 align:middle line:84%
the images of the points are
different from each other.

00:29:14.570 --> 00:29:16.730 align:middle line:90%
They stay spread out.

00:29:16.730 --> 00:29:19.330 align:middle line:84%
And in the continuous case,
we said something else,

00:29:19.330 --> 00:29:21.810 align:middle line:84%
that if you have a
bunch of these peaks,

00:29:21.810 --> 00:29:24.450 align:middle line:84%
then in most directions
when you project,

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:27.370 align:middle line:84%
things kind average out
and are spaced evenly.

00:29:27.370 --> 00:29:30.890 align:middle line:84%
And how are those two things
connected to each other?

00:29:30.890 --> 00:29:32.940 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:29:32.940 --> 00:29:37.290 align:middle line:90%


00:29:37.290 --> 00:29:39.930 align:middle line:84%
So one part of it, I
think, is kind of clear.

00:29:39.930 --> 00:29:42.010 align:middle line:84%
So one part of it I
can explain easily,

00:29:42.010 --> 00:29:43.930 align:middle line:84%
and then this won't
be everything.

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:49.730 align:middle line:84%
But if my balls were
arranged in such a way

00:29:49.730 --> 00:29:58.090 align:middle line:84%
that when I projected they went
on top of each other, so then

00:29:58.090 --> 00:30:00.470 align:middle line:84%
the projection of my function
would be really big here,

00:30:00.470 --> 00:30:02.840 align:middle line:84%
and then it would be 0, and
it would be really big here,

00:30:02.840 --> 00:30:05.293 align:middle line:84%
and it would be 0, and then
it would be really big there.

00:30:05.293 --> 00:30:06.460 align:middle line:90%
So that would not be smooth.

00:30:06.460 --> 00:30:08.760 align:middle line:84%
It would be
oscillating violently.

00:30:08.760 --> 00:30:11.720 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a direction,
which is bad in the sense

00:30:11.720 --> 00:30:14.393 align:middle line:84%
that these balls are landing
on top of each other,

00:30:14.393 --> 00:30:16.310 align:middle line:84%
then it will be bad for
this analysis problem.

00:30:16.310 --> 00:30:22.520 align:middle line:90%


00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:27.640 align:middle line:84%
But a set could be bad for this
analysis problem in another way.

00:30:27.640 --> 00:30:32.120 align:middle line:84%
There could be two balls over
here, and one ball over there,

00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:35.180 align:middle line:84%
and two balls over here,
and one ball over there,

00:30:35.180 --> 00:30:38.120 align:middle line:84%
and then the density would
still be oscillating a lot,

00:30:38.120 --> 00:30:40.370 align:middle line:84%
but the image wouldn't
be particularly small.

00:30:40.370 --> 00:30:44.100 align:middle line:90%


00:30:44.100 --> 00:30:47.400 align:middle line:84%
So that will require
some additional ideas.

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:49.280 align:middle line:84%
But it still turns
out to be the case

00:30:49.280 --> 00:30:54.720 align:middle line:84%
that trying to prove stuff
about this, the ideas, the ideas

00:30:54.720 --> 00:30:58.900 align:middle line:84%
from ruling out this
case are related.

00:30:58.900 --> 00:30:59.993 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:59.993 --> 00:31:03.180 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It's probably the
next-- exactly the problem

00:31:03.180 --> 00:31:05.620 align:middle line:84%
relating these two,
but is there an analog

00:31:05.620 --> 00:31:08.460 align:middle line:90%
for these distributions?

00:31:08.460 --> 00:31:10.380 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:31:10.380 --> 00:31:10.940 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:10.940 --> 00:31:13.960 align:middle line:84%
There's an analog
for distributions.

00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:16.700 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, what if
f was a distribution instead

00:31:16.700 --> 00:31:17.320 align:middle line:90%
of a function?

00:31:17.320 --> 00:31:20.660 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it was something
messier than being an L2.

00:31:20.660 --> 00:31:24.430 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, you could
still say things.

00:31:24.430 --> 00:31:28.260 align:middle line:90%


00:31:28.260 --> 00:31:34.660 align:middle line:84%
I wasn't planning-- so I
think all of those questions

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:38.820 align:middle line:84%
you can reduce to something
about how balls get projected.

00:31:38.820 --> 00:31:41.060 align:middle line:84%
And then if you want to,
you can say something

00:31:41.060 --> 00:31:42.360 align:middle line:90%
about distributions.

00:31:42.360 --> 00:31:50.940 align:middle line:90%


00:31:50.940 --> 00:31:53.660 align:middle line:84%
So the next character in the
story I wanted to mention to you

00:31:53.660 --> 00:31:57.660 align:middle line:84%
is the Fourier transform,
that in this continuous setup,

00:31:57.660 --> 00:32:00.280 align:middle line:84%
there's a very close connection
between this projection

00:32:00.280 --> 00:32:02.640 align:middle line:84%
operation and the
Fourier transform.

00:32:02.640 --> 00:32:05.820 align:middle line:84%
And that brings Fourier
analysis into projection theory.

00:32:05.820 --> 00:32:48.160 align:middle line:90%


00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:51.480 align:middle line:84%
So the connection with
the Fourier transform

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:54.160 align:middle line:90%
is the following lemma.

00:32:54.160 --> 00:32:55.560 align:middle line:90%
Well, actually let me make a--

00:32:55.560 --> 00:33:00.360 align:middle line:90%


00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:02.180 align:middle line:90%
so here's our space Rd.

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:06.060 align:middle line:84%
And in there, we have our
subspace v. So our function f

00:33:06.060 --> 00:33:07.340 align:middle line:90%
lives on R to the d.

00:33:07.340 --> 00:33:11.180 align:middle line:84%
And the projection
of f lives on v.

00:33:11.180 --> 00:33:14.460 align:middle line:84%
Now, how does the
Fourier transform work?

00:33:14.460 --> 00:33:16.190 align:middle line:90%
So here's Fourier space.

00:33:16.190 --> 00:33:20.180 align:middle line:90%


00:33:20.180 --> 00:33:22.840 align:middle line:84%
So Fourier space
is also R to the d.

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:26.140 align:middle line:84%
So f hat will live
on R to the d.

00:33:26.140 --> 00:33:32.140 align:middle line:84%
And the Fourier transform
of something on v

00:33:32.140 --> 00:33:34.300 align:middle line:90%
lives on v as well.

00:33:34.300 --> 00:33:36.900 align:middle line:84%
So in this R to the
d, I'll draw here.

00:33:36.900 --> 00:33:38.580 align:middle line:90%
I'll call it v hat.

00:33:38.580 --> 00:33:41.040 align:middle line:84%
I guess if we wanted to, we
could call this R to the d hat.

00:33:41.040 --> 00:33:43.660 align:middle line:90%


00:33:43.660 --> 00:33:49.500 align:middle line:84%
So if I have this
function, Rd to c, then f

00:33:49.500 --> 00:33:54.970 align:middle line:84%
hat is a function R to
the d hat goes to c.

00:33:54.970 --> 00:33:59.210 align:middle line:84%
The projection of f is
a function from v to c.

00:33:59.210 --> 00:34:03.830 align:middle line:84%
And the projection of f hat
is a function from v hat to c.

00:34:03.830 --> 00:34:09.290 align:middle line:90%


00:34:09.290 --> 00:34:10.810 align:middle line:84%
And then the lemma
about how they

00:34:10.810 --> 00:34:15.730 align:middle line:84%
are related is that if you
take the projection Fourier

00:34:15.730 --> 00:34:44.570 align:middle line:84%
transform of c, it's just
f hat c for any c and v.

00:34:44.570 --> 00:34:49.400 align:middle line:84%
So let me write down the
sketch, the proof of this lemma.

00:34:49.400 --> 00:34:53.550 align:middle line:90%


00:34:53.550 --> 00:34:55.370 align:middle line:90%
It has a simple explanation.

00:34:55.370 --> 00:34:57.950 align:middle line:90%


00:34:57.950 --> 00:35:04.470 align:middle line:84%
So pi v f hat of c is
the integral over v pi v

00:35:04.470 --> 00:35:10.050 align:middle line:84%
f of y e to the
minus i xi dot y dy.

00:35:10.050 --> 00:35:14.830 align:middle line:90%


00:35:14.830 --> 00:35:17.110 align:middle line:90%
Now, what is pi v of f?

00:35:17.110 --> 00:35:19.010 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's the integral
over the fiber.

00:35:19.010 --> 00:35:25.870 align:middle line:84%
So integral over v, integral
over pi inverse of y f

00:35:25.870 --> 00:35:33.710 align:middle line:84%
of x d volume of the fiber e
to the minus i xi dot y dy.

00:35:33.710 --> 00:35:38.310 align:middle line:90%


00:35:38.310 --> 00:35:40.930 align:middle line:84%
And now notice that we
have a double integral.

00:35:40.930 --> 00:35:42.970 align:middle line:84%
We're integrating over
the fiber and over y.

00:35:42.970 --> 00:35:44.970 align:middle line:84%
So if you put those
together, you just get a dx.

00:35:44.970 --> 00:35:49.290 align:middle line:90%


00:35:49.290 --> 00:35:55.130 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happens to this
e to the minus i xi dot y?

00:35:55.130 --> 00:36:03.690 align:middle line:84%
So remark that
since x is in pi v

00:36:03.690 --> 00:36:13.210 align:middle line:84%
inverse of y, that tells us that
x minus y is perpendicular to v.

00:36:13.210 --> 00:36:15.175 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The
inverse is on the pi.

00:36:15.175 --> 00:36:16.550 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: It
goes on the pi.

00:36:16.550 --> 00:36:17.050 align:middle line:90%
Thanks.

00:36:17.050 --> 00:36:27.650 align:middle line:90%


00:36:27.650 --> 00:36:29.970 align:middle line:90%
Over here is y.

00:36:29.970 --> 00:36:31.410 align:middle line:90%
Here's the fiber.

00:36:31.410 --> 00:36:33.770 align:middle line:90%
And in our fiber, we have x.

00:36:33.770 --> 00:36:37.850 align:middle line:84%
So x minus y is
perpendicular to v.

00:36:37.850 --> 00:36:44.370 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, we also
know that the frequency xi

00:36:44.370 --> 00:36:50.040 align:middle line:84%
is in v. xi is in this
copy of v over here.

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:54.650 align:middle line:84%
So x minus y is
perpendicular to xi.

00:36:54.650 --> 00:37:00.910 align:middle line:84%
x minus y, x minus
y dot xi is 0.

00:37:00.910 --> 00:37:05.800 align:middle line:90%


00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:11.160 align:middle line:84%
So that means I can change
this xi dot y for xi dot x.

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:13.380 align:middle line:84%
And I put these
volume forms together.

00:37:13.380 --> 00:37:16.400 align:middle line:84%
I have the integral of
f of x e to the minus i

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:19.750 align:middle line:84%
xi dot x dx, which
is f hat of x.

00:37:19.750 --> 00:37:33.560 align:middle line:90%


00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:34.760 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:37.200 align:middle line:84%
So that's an interesting
connection between projections

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:38.720 align:middle line:90%
and Fourier analysis.

00:37:38.720 --> 00:37:41.880 align:middle line:84%
And it was used classically to
solve the problem of recovering

00:37:41.880 --> 00:37:43.980 align:middle line:90%
a density from the CAT scan.

00:37:43.980 --> 00:37:47.380 align:middle line:84%
So mathematically, the problem
would be you're given pi v of f.

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:50.580 align:middle line:84%
For every v, you
want to recover f.

00:37:50.580 --> 00:37:54.980 align:middle line:84%
And the way you can do it
is because of this formula,

00:37:54.980 --> 00:37:56.002 align:middle line:90%
you can recover--

00:37:56.002 --> 00:37:58.460 align:middle line:84%
if you're given-- if you know
all the pi v of f's, then you

00:37:58.460 --> 00:38:00.540 align:middle line:84%
can compute their
Fourier transform.

00:38:00.540 --> 00:38:04.538 align:middle line:84%
So you can compute f hat of
xi for all the xi in v hat.

00:38:04.538 --> 00:38:07.080 align:middle line:84%
Well, you have all the different
v's, so you put it together.

00:38:07.080 --> 00:38:08.900 align:middle line:90%
Now you have computed f hat.

00:38:08.900 --> 00:38:10.040 align:middle line:90%
So you can find f.

00:38:10.040 --> 00:38:16.780 align:middle line:90%


00:38:16.780 --> 00:38:17.380 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:38:17.380 --> 00:38:19.300 align:middle line:84%
But this connection with
the Fourier transform

00:38:19.300 --> 00:38:23.140 align:middle line:84%
also can be used to study this
continuous projection theory

00:38:23.140 --> 00:38:23.960 align:middle line:90%
problem.

00:38:23.960 --> 00:38:26.600 align:middle line:84%
And it's used to prove
this proposition here.

00:38:26.600 --> 00:38:29.620 align:middle line:90%


00:38:29.620 --> 00:38:30.460 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:38:30.460 --> 00:38:31.460 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: What is v hat?

00:38:31.460 --> 00:38:32.420 align:middle line:90%
What's v?

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:35.108 align:middle line:90%


00:38:35.108 --> 00:38:36.400 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, thank you.

00:38:36.400 --> 00:38:41.940 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, what's the
difference between v hat and v?

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:44.320 align:middle line:84%
I'm not sure it was
helpful to put the hats.

00:38:44.320 --> 00:38:47.160 align:middle line:84%
It might be clearer
if we remove the hats.

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:48.840 align:middle line:84%
So here's another
copy of R to the d,

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:50.860 align:middle line:90%
where the variable xi lives.

00:38:50.860 --> 00:38:57.120 align:middle line:84%
And here's the same space
v. And maybe it's clearer

00:38:57.120 --> 00:38:58.270 align:middle line:90%
to remove all these hats.

00:38:58.270 --> 00:39:30.040 align:middle line:90%


00:39:30.040 --> 00:39:33.240 align:middle line:84%
So we mentioned before that this
continuous problem has something

00:39:33.240 --> 00:39:35.600 align:middle line:84%
to do with what happens
when you take balls

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:39.040 align:middle line:84%
and you project the balls
instead of projecting points.

00:39:39.040 --> 00:39:40.800 align:middle line:84%
And it's a little
tricky to formulate

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:43.830 align:middle line:84%
exactly what the question should
be about projecting balls.

00:39:43.830 --> 00:39:46.630 align:middle line:84%
I want to take you
through the first steps

00:39:46.630 --> 00:39:49.430 align:middle line:84%
and just see why it's
a little bit tricky

00:39:49.430 --> 00:39:51.210 align:middle line:84%
and what direction
we're going to go in.

00:39:51.210 --> 00:40:15.930 align:middle line:90%


00:40:15.930 --> 00:40:27.070 align:middle line:84%
So I have projection theory for
unit balls, maybe first steps

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:28.170 align:middle line:90%
or something like that.

00:40:28.170 --> 00:40:36.830 align:middle line:90%


00:40:36.830 --> 00:40:43.490 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that x is
a set of disjoint unit

00:40:43.490 --> 00:40:49.620 align:middle line:84%
balls in a big ball
of radius R in R2.

00:40:49.620 --> 00:40:59.370 align:middle line:90%


00:40:59.370 --> 00:41:00.850 align:middle line:84%
So we could consider
the projection

00:41:00.850 --> 00:41:01.870 align:middle line:90%
in different directions.

00:41:01.870 --> 00:41:06.610 align:middle line:84%
And we'll have sets of unit
intervals, more or less.

00:41:06.610 --> 00:41:09.130 align:middle line:84%
And we could ask for
the number of directions

00:41:09.130 --> 00:41:11.085 align:middle line:84%
where something or
another happens.

00:41:11.085 --> 00:41:12.710 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let's step
back a little bit.

00:41:12.710 --> 00:41:15.610 align:middle line:84%
So OK, so we have a
set of unit balls.

00:41:15.610 --> 00:41:18.690 align:middle line:84%
And in this context, I'm going
to use the absolute value

00:41:18.690 --> 00:41:25.050 align:middle line:84%
of x to denote the area of x,
or volume in whatever dimension.

00:41:25.050 --> 00:41:28.930 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully, that will be
helpful and not confusing

00:41:28.930 --> 00:41:30.253 align:middle line:90%
compared with before.

00:41:30.253 --> 00:41:31.670 align:middle line:84%
If you have a bunch
of unit balls,

00:41:31.670 --> 00:41:33.045 align:middle line:84%
its area is more
or less the same

00:41:33.045 --> 00:41:35.690 align:middle line:90%
as the number of unit balls.

00:41:35.690 --> 00:41:42.110 align:middle line:84%
So then if we look at
pi v of x, that would

00:41:42.110 --> 00:41:48.290 align:middle line:90%
be the length of pi v of x.

00:41:48.290 --> 00:41:51.910 align:middle line:84%
So now I want to make a question
like the Szemerédi-Trotter

00:41:51.910 --> 00:41:52.790 align:middle line:90%
question.

00:41:52.790 --> 00:41:54.630 align:middle line:84%
So I could look at
the set of directions

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:59.510 align:middle line:84%
where the projection has
length less than s maybe.

00:41:59.510 --> 00:42:02.270 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I'll do that.

00:42:02.270 --> 00:42:12.750 align:middle line:84%
So Es of x might be set of
v Gr 1, 2, so that pi v of x

00:42:12.750 --> 00:42:16.150 align:middle line:90%
has length at most s.

00:42:16.150 --> 00:42:19.830 align:middle line:84%
But it would now be silly to
ask for the number of elements

00:42:19.830 --> 00:42:20.990 align:middle line:90%
of this thing.

00:42:20.990 --> 00:42:22.510 align:middle line:84%
This thing is very
likely infinite,

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:24.270 align:middle line:84%
if it's not empty,
because if you

00:42:24.270 --> 00:42:26.470 align:middle line:84%
make a tiny perturbation
in v, it will have

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:30.190 align:middle line:90%
a tiny effect on pi v of x.

00:42:30.190 --> 00:42:33.750 align:middle line:84%
So there's a natural
discretization.

00:42:33.750 --> 00:42:41.060 align:middle line:84%
So we know that if the angle
between v1 and v2 is less than

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:51.220 align:middle line:84%
1/R, then pi v1 of x and pi
v2 of x are basically the same

00:42:51.220 --> 00:42:52.980 align:middle line:90%
as each other.

00:42:52.980 --> 00:42:55.920 align:middle line:84%
And so it doesn't make a lot of
sense to count them separately.

00:42:55.920 --> 00:42:59.660 align:middle line:90%


00:42:59.660 --> 00:43:02.122 align:middle line:84%
So if we want to
count something,

00:43:02.122 --> 00:43:03.580 align:middle line:84%
one trick we could
make is we could

00:43:03.580 --> 00:43:16.060 align:middle line:84%
have this fancy v be a set
of R v's in Grassmann 1, 2

00:43:16.060 --> 00:43:17.150 align:middle line:90%
that are evenly spaced.

00:43:17.150 --> 00:43:20.980 align:middle line:90%


00:43:20.980 --> 00:43:22.710 align:middle line:90%
So I just draw--

00:43:22.710 --> 00:43:25.355 align:middle line:90%


00:43:25.355 --> 00:43:29.580 align:middle line:84%
oh, sorry-- r different lines
through the origin evenly spaced

00:43:29.580 --> 00:43:32.460 align:middle line:90%
at an angle of about 1/R.

00:43:32.460 --> 00:43:39.320 align:middle line:84%
And then my new
question will be,

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:48.440 align:middle line:84%
if x is a set of disjoint unit
balls in the ball of radius R

00:43:48.440 --> 00:43:52.540 align:middle line:90%
and R2, then estimate--

00:43:52.540 --> 00:43:55.280 align:middle line:90%


00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:58.427 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so actually, let's
change this definition.

00:43:58.427 --> 00:44:00.760 align:middle line:84%
We're not going to count all
of the v's, but we're going

00:44:00.760 --> 00:44:04.280 align:middle line:90%
to count the ones in this set.

00:44:04.280 --> 00:44:08.280 align:middle line:84%
And that's a more fair
comparison to before.

00:44:08.280 --> 00:44:16.960 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to estimate the
size of Es of x in terms of s

00:44:16.960 --> 00:44:18.578 align:middle line:90%
and the size of x.

00:44:18.578 --> 00:44:20.870 align:middle line:84%
And we can compare it to the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem.

00:44:20.870 --> 00:44:30.052 align:middle line:90%


00:44:30.052 --> 00:44:32.540 align:middle line:84%
So we could ask, is
it still always true

00:44:32.540 --> 00:44:35.780 align:middle line:84%
that this is bounded by
that expression there?

00:44:35.780 --> 00:44:36.840 align:middle line:90%
I'll write that down.

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:54.140 align:middle line:90%


00:44:54.140 --> 00:45:03.060 align:middle line:84%
Is it true that Es of x
is bounded by 1 plus S

00:45:03.060 --> 00:45:04.200 align:middle line:90%
squared over x?

00:45:04.200 --> 00:45:06.940 align:middle line:90%


00:45:06.940 --> 00:45:08.500 align:middle line:90%
And this is not true.

00:45:08.500 --> 00:45:11.500 align:middle line:84%
There's a configuration of
unit balls where Es of x

00:45:11.500 --> 00:45:12.840 align:middle line:90%
is much bigger than s.

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:15.420 align:middle line:90%


00:45:15.420 --> 00:45:17.340 align:middle line:84%
What can we do with
unit balls that

00:45:17.340 --> 00:45:20.110 align:middle line:84%
sort of wasn't relevant before
when we had perfect points?

00:45:20.110 --> 00:45:28.540 align:middle line:90%


00:45:28.540 --> 00:45:32.170 align:middle line:84%
What other example
might we look at?

00:45:32.170 --> 00:45:33.370 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, what do you think?

00:45:33.370 --> 00:45:36.070 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: You could integrate
functions over them?

00:45:36.070 --> 00:45:37.070 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: We could.

00:45:37.070 --> 00:45:39.550 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so we can integrate
functions over them.

00:45:39.550 --> 00:45:43.710 align:middle line:90%


00:45:43.710 --> 00:45:45.610 align:middle line:84%
So here's a configuration
of unit balls.

00:45:45.610 --> 00:45:47.250 align:middle line:84%
It kind of doesn't
have an analog when

00:45:47.250 --> 00:45:48.610 align:middle line:90%
you're just looking at points.

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:50.277 align:middle line:84%
But what we're going
to do is we're just

00:45:50.277 --> 00:45:52.690 align:middle line:84%
going to pack them
into a larger ball.

00:45:52.690 --> 00:45:55.690 align:middle line:90%
So here's the example.

00:45:55.690 --> 00:45:58.850 align:middle line:90%
So here's our big ball.

00:45:58.850 --> 00:46:02.250 align:middle line:84%
And then inside of it,
I have a smaller ball.

00:46:02.250 --> 00:46:05.700 align:middle line:84%
And I pack the smaller
ball full of unit balls.

00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:10.890 align:middle line:90%


00:46:10.890 --> 00:46:11.870 align:middle line:90%
So that's x.

00:46:11.870 --> 00:46:15.690 align:middle line:90%


00:46:15.690 --> 00:46:18.170 align:middle line:84%
So the area of x or the
number of unit balls

00:46:18.170 --> 00:46:20.290 align:middle line:90%
is around n squared.

00:46:20.290 --> 00:46:23.370 align:middle line:84%
And no matter what direction
I project this thing

00:46:23.370 --> 00:46:33.270 align:middle line:84%
in, it's going to fill in an
interval of length n, about n.

00:46:33.270 --> 00:46:40.590 align:middle line:84%
So for every v, I'm going
to have pi v of x around n,

00:46:40.590 --> 00:46:41.710 align:middle line:90%
which is x to the 1/2.

00:46:41.710 --> 00:46:47.550 align:middle line:90%


00:46:47.550 --> 00:46:55.510 align:middle line:84%
So if I make s equal to x
to the 1/2, or a bit less,

00:46:55.510 --> 00:47:03.510 align:middle line:84%
then Es of x is the whole
thing, every direction.

00:47:03.510 --> 00:47:08.610 align:middle line:84%
And so the size of Es of
x is R. It's all of them.

00:47:08.610 --> 00:47:10.710 align:middle line:84%
It's as big as it
could possibly be.

00:47:10.710 --> 00:47:14.190 align:middle line:84%
Whereas if you plug in s is
the square root of x here,

00:47:14.190 --> 00:47:15.910 align:middle line:90%
you would get 1.

00:47:15.910 --> 00:47:17.810 align:middle line:84%
So it's actually
as bad as possible.

00:47:17.810 --> 00:47:19.830 align:middle line:84%
The prediction of
Szemerédi-Trotter is 1,

00:47:19.830 --> 00:47:21.450 align:middle line:90%
and the truth is everything.

00:47:21.450 --> 00:47:35.130 align:middle line:90%


00:47:35.130 --> 00:47:38.290 align:middle line:84%
So these small
balls are not really

00:47:38.290 --> 00:47:40.810 align:middle line:84%
behaving like points
because of the fact

00:47:40.810 --> 00:47:44.930 align:middle line:84%
that they've been packed
so densely into a big ball.

00:47:44.930 --> 00:47:49.150 align:middle line:90%
And so if we--

00:47:49.150 --> 00:47:51.770 align:middle line:84%
it is perfectly reasonable
to analyze this situation

00:47:51.770 --> 00:47:52.910 align:middle line:90%
and answer this question.

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:54.430 align:middle line:90%
We will do that in this class.

00:47:54.430 --> 00:47:57.330 align:middle line:84%
There is an answer to it,
and it's worth knowing.

00:47:57.330 --> 00:48:01.430 align:middle line:84%
However, as you insist that
these small balls are spread

00:48:01.430 --> 00:48:03.650 align:middle line:84%
apart farther and
farther, then they

00:48:03.650 --> 00:48:06.590 align:middle line:84%
start to behave more and
more like ideal points.

00:48:06.590 --> 00:48:08.230 align:middle line:90%
And eventually, this is true.

00:48:08.230 --> 00:48:11.370 align:middle line:90%


00:48:11.370 --> 00:48:25.430 align:middle line:84%
So a goal of this part is to add
hypotheses that the set of balls

00:48:25.430 --> 00:48:32.530 align:middle line:84%
is spread out, and then
get stronger conclusions.

00:48:32.530 --> 00:48:40.270 align:middle line:90%


00:48:40.270 --> 00:48:42.590 align:middle line:84%
And probably next class,
we will play around

00:48:42.590 --> 00:48:45.030 align:middle line:84%
with how to state some
precise hypotheses

00:48:45.030 --> 00:48:47.100 align:middle line:84%
and what kind of
conclusions we might expect.

00:48:47.100 --> 00:48:49.870 align:middle line:90%


00:48:49.870 --> 00:48:52.630 align:middle line:84%
But the big progress
that I referred to

00:48:52.630 --> 00:48:54.630 align:middle line:84%
at the beginning of
the class in the field

00:48:54.630 --> 00:48:58.630 align:middle line:84%
is that in the last couple
of years, people proved,

00:48:58.630 --> 00:49:01.150 align:middle line:84%
let's say, the main
conjecture about this question

00:49:01.150 --> 00:49:04.670 align:middle line:90%
for unit balls in R2.

00:49:04.670 --> 00:49:07.390 align:middle line:84%
And we'll try to flesh it
out, because you could imagine

00:49:07.390 --> 00:49:09.310 align:middle line:90%
many different hypotheses.

00:49:09.310 --> 00:49:13.310 align:middle line:84%
But I think the theory gives a
fairly complete picture of how

00:49:13.310 --> 00:49:16.710 align:middle line:90%
this works for balls in R2.

00:49:16.710 --> 00:49:19.070 align:middle line:84%
Different hypotheses about
how spread out they are,

00:49:19.070 --> 00:49:23.220 align:middle line:84%
and what you can conclude about
how often the projections have

00:49:23.220 --> 00:49:24.840 align:middle line:84%
things piled on
top of each other.

00:49:24.840 --> 00:49:38.060 align:middle line:90%


00:49:38.060 --> 00:49:41.720 align:middle line:84%
Now, there are many
variations on these questions.

00:49:41.720 --> 00:49:44.320 align:middle line:84%
And because this one is a
little bit difficult to state,

00:49:44.320 --> 00:49:46.100 align:middle line:84%
I thought I'd mention
one other, which

00:49:46.100 --> 00:49:47.480 align:middle line:90%
is a beautiful open problem.

00:49:47.480 --> 00:49:50.420 align:middle line:90%
And it's pretty clean to state.

00:49:50.420 --> 00:49:53.160 align:middle line:84%
And it will let me explain
one of the key difficulties.

00:49:53.160 --> 00:49:57.004 align:middle line:90%


00:49:57.004 --> 00:50:01.300 align:middle line:84%
So these questions make
sense over any field.

00:50:01.300 --> 00:50:03.860 align:middle line:84%
I started with the real numbers,
because I was kind of used

00:50:03.860 --> 00:50:06.020 align:middle line:90%
to it, because I'm an analyst.

00:50:06.020 --> 00:50:10.198 align:middle line:84%
But you could ask about any
field, any vector space.

00:50:10.198 --> 00:50:12.490 align:middle line:84%
And actually, a very interesting
case is finite fields.

00:50:12.490 --> 00:50:28.460 align:middle line:90%


00:50:28.460 --> 00:50:34.030 align:middle line:84%
So the cousin problem
over finite fields.

00:50:34.030 --> 00:50:43.020 align:middle line:90%


00:50:43.020 --> 00:50:49.110 align:middle line:84%
So let's say Fq is the
finite field with q elements.

00:50:49.110 --> 00:50:52.480 align:middle line:90%


00:50:52.480 --> 00:50:58.840 align:middle line:84%
And if I write Fp, that
will mean p is a prime.

00:50:58.840 --> 00:51:01.740 align:middle line:84%
So it's Fp of a field with
a prime number of elements.

00:51:01.740 --> 00:51:03.560 align:middle line:84%
And Fq is a general
finite field.

00:51:03.560 --> 00:51:04.880 align:middle line:90%
q will be some prime power.

00:51:04.880 --> 00:51:09.440 align:middle line:90%


00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:11.520 align:middle line:90%
So here's our question.

00:51:11.520 --> 00:51:15.320 align:middle line:84%
So now I should say, what
is an orthogonal projection?

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:17.640 align:middle line:84%
So it's not hard to
say what a subspace is.

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:20.120 align:middle line:84%
Over finite fields, we
don't have, obviously,

00:51:20.120 --> 00:51:26.420 align:middle line:84%
a notion of orthogonality,
but orthogonality isn't really

00:51:26.420 --> 00:51:27.245 align:middle line:90%
the crucial thing.

00:51:27.245 --> 00:51:28.620 align:middle line:84%
The crucial thing
is just that we

00:51:28.620 --> 00:51:31.940 align:middle line:84%
have a lot of linear maps
from our vector space

00:51:31.940 --> 00:51:34.180 align:middle line:84%
to a lower dimensional
vector space.

00:51:34.180 --> 00:51:36.900 align:middle line:84%
So we're really looking at
all the possible linear maps.

00:51:36.900 --> 00:51:39.380 align:middle line:84%
So in terms of what are
the possible projections,

00:51:39.380 --> 00:51:42.900 align:middle line:84%
I can parameterize
them just like this.

00:51:42.900 --> 00:51:50.940 align:middle line:84%
So if t is in Fq, pi t will be
a map from Fq squared to Fq.

00:51:50.940 --> 00:51:58.660 align:middle line:84%
And pi t of x1, x2 is
just x1 plus t times x2.

00:51:58.660 --> 00:52:00.310 align:middle line:84%
So those are a bunch
of linear maps.

00:52:00.310 --> 00:52:03.300 align:middle line:90%


00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:05.820 align:middle line:84%
And actually, you
might say, why don't I

00:52:05.820 --> 00:52:07.240 align:middle line:90%
write all the linear maps?

00:52:07.240 --> 00:52:09.680 align:middle line:90%
I could have t1 x1 plus t2 x2.

00:52:09.680 --> 00:52:12.260 align:middle line:90%
Those are all the linear maps.

00:52:12.260 --> 00:52:16.890 align:middle line:84%
But if you multiply t1
and t2 by the same factor,

00:52:16.890 --> 00:52:19.610 align:middle line:84%
then you've just
taken a linear map,

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:23.530 align:middle line:84%
and then composed with a
linear map from Fp to itself.

00:52:23.530 --> 00:52:26.290 align:middle line:84%
So those are all going
to be equivalent for us.

00:52:26.290 --> 00:52:31.930 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why we just set
this to be 1, and let this be t.

00:52:31.930 --> 00:52:41.610 align:middle line:84%
So now let's say x is in
Fq squared and Es of x is

00:52:41.610 --> 00:52:42.930 align:middle line:90%
the set of t.

00:52:42.930 --> 00:52:49.330 align:middle line:84%
So the t just live in Fq with
the property that pi t of x

00:52:49.330 --> 00:52:52.718 align:middle line:90%
is at most s.

00:52:52.718 --> 00:52:54.260 align:middle line:84%
And now we can ask
the same question.

00:52:54.260 --> 00:52:58.850 align:middle line:90%


00:52:58.850 --> 00:53:12.610 align:middle line:84%
Question-- estimate the size
of Es of x in terms of s

00:53:12.610 --> 00:53:16.370 align:middle line:84%
and x, ideally, and
I guess maybe q.

00:53:16.370 --> 00:53:25.430 align:middle line:90%


00:53:25.430 --> 00:53:29.710 align:middle line:84%
Now, an integer grid still
makes sense over a finite field.

00:53:29.710 --> 00:53:35.070 align:middle line:84%
And so it works the same way
as in Szemerédi and Trotter.

00:53:35.070 --> 00:53:37.710 align:middle line:84%
And over the prime
fields, that's

00:53:37.710 --> 00:53:39.870 align:middle line:90%
the best example that we know.

00:53:39.870 --> 00:53:46.830 align:middle line:84%
So there is a conjecture,
if x is in Fp squared--

00:53:46.830 --> 00:53:49.010 align:middle line:84%
and p is always prime,
but it's important here,

00:53:49.010 --> 00:53:52.630 align:middle line:90%
so I will add it--

00:53:52.630 --> 00:53:59.150 align:middle line:84%
then the size of Es of
x is bounded by 1 plus

00:53:59.150 --> 00:54:00.490 align:middle line:90%
s squared over x.

00:54:00.490 --> 00:54:08.190 align:middle line:90%


00:54:08.190 --> 00:54:10.110 align:middle line:90%
Matching that.

00:54:10.110 --> 00:54:18.090 align:middle line:84%
But this is not
true in Fq squared.

00:54:18.090 --> 00:54:21.740 align:middle line:90%
q is not prime.

00:54:21.740 --> 00:54:33.914 align:middle line:90%


00:54:33.914 --> 00:54:35.680 align:middle line:90%
So let me show you an example.

00:54:35.680 --> 00:54:39.290 align:middle line:90%


00:54:39.290 --> 00:54:42.340 align:middle line:84%
And this example plays a
big role in the theory.

00:54:42.340 --> 00:54:58.290 align:middle line:90%


00:54:58.290 --> 00:55:01.690 align:middle line:90%
So here's the example.

00:55:01.690 --> 00:55:04.050 align:middle line:90%
Suppose that q is p squared.

00:55:04.050 --> 00:55:05.990 align:middle line:84%
There are similar examples
for higher powers,

00:55:05.990 --> 00:55:09.730 align:middle line:84%
but this is just
simple concrete.

00:55:09.730 --> 00:55:14.020 align:middle line:90%
So Fp is a subset of Fq.

00:55:14.020 --> 00:55:16.520 align:middle line:90%
It's a subfield of Fq.

00:55:16.520 --> 00:55:21.200 align:middle line:84%
And our set x is going
to be Fp squared, which

00:55:21.200 --> 00:55:24.720 align:middle line:90%
is a subset of Fq squared.

00:55:24.720 --> 00:55:27.830 align:middle line:84%
Cardinality of x is p
squared, which is q.

00:55:27.830 --> 00:55:31.400 align:middle line:90%


00:55:31.400 --> 00:55:39.280 align:middle line:84%
So now notice that
if t is also in Fp

00:55:39.280 --> 00:55:47.440 align:middle line:84%
and x is in x, then pi t of x,
which is x1 plus t times x2,

00:55:47.440 --> 00:55:51.120 align:middle line:84%
well, all of these characters,
I've assumed to be in Fp.

00:55:51.120 --> 00:55:52.202 align:middle line:90%
And Fp is a field.

00:55:52.202 --> 00:55:54.660 align:middle line:84%
So it's closed under addition,
closed under multiplication.

00:55:54.660 --> 00:55:55.710 align:middle line:90%
So this is in Fp.

00:55:55.710 --> 00:55:59.520 align:middle line:90%


00:55:59.520 --> 00:56:09.740 align:middle line:84%
So that tells me that if t
is in Fp, pi T of x is Fp--

00:56:09.740 --> 00:56:10.880 align:middle line:90%
is contained in Fp.

00:56:10.880 --> 00:56:12.380 align:middle line:90%
It's actually all of it.

00:56:12.380 --> 00:56:17.980 align:middle line:84%
And so the size of pi
t of x is at most p,

00:56:17.980 --> 00:56:21.720 align:middle line:84%
which is q to the 1/2, which is
much smaller than the size of x.

00:56:21.720 --> 00:56:27.980 align:middle line:90%


00:56:27.980 --> 00:56:39.460 align:middle line:84%
So we conclude that the size
of Ep of x is at least p.

00:56:39.460 --> 00:56:47.220 align:middle line:84%
So there are p traces t
that all lie in Ep of x.

00:56:47.220 --> 00:56:50.742 align:middle line:84%
And that's much bigger than
the bound in the conjecture

00:56:50.742 --> 00:56:52.450 align:middle line:84%
for what should happen
over prime fields.

00:56:52.450 --> 00:56:55.780 align:middle line:90%


00:56:55.780 --> 00:56:58.552 align:middle line:84%
So if we were to plug in
these numbers up here,

00:56:58.552 --> 00:57:02.620 align:middle line:84%
s would be p, which is
the square root of q,

00:57:02.620 --> 00:57:04.100 align:middle line:90%
and x would be q.

00:57:04.100 --> 00:57:06.920 align:middle line:90%
So this would be y.

00:57:06.920 --> 00:57:09.060 align:middle line:84%
Over prime fields, this
should be order of 1.

00:57:09.060 --> 00:57:11.340 align:middle line:84%
But over this not prime
field, it's much bigger.

00:57:11.340 --> 00:57:20.284 align:middle line:90%


00:57:20.284 --> 00:57:23.760 align:middle line:84%
So this shows that
projection theory is also

00:57:23.760 --> 00:57:25.500 align:middle line:90%
connected to some--

00:57:25.500 --> 00:57:28.080 align:middle line:84%
I don't know-- algebra,
algebraic structure questions

00:57:28.080 --> 00:57:31.180 align:middle line:84%
of whether fields
have subfields.

00:57:31.180 --> 00:57:34.080 align:middle line:90%


00:57:34.080 --> 00:57:38.120 align:middle line:90%
And this issue, which is--

00:57:38.120 --> 00:57:39.960 align:middle line:90%
so this is an open conjecture.

00:57:39.960 --> 00:57:42.720 align:middle line:90%
And it's hard for two reasons.

00:57:42.720 --> 00:57:45.672 align:middle line:84%
The first reason is,
well, you look at it.

00:57:45.672 --> 00:57:47.380 align:middle line:84%
You say, OK, it's like
Szemerédi-Trotter,

00:57:47.380 --> 00:57:48.828 align:middle line:90%
but over a prime field.

00:57:48.828 --> 00:57:51.120 align:middle line:84%
So I should try to take the
proof of Szemerédi-Trotter.

00:57:51.120 --> 00:57:53.680 align:middle line:84%
And that proof
completely breaks down.

00:57:53.680 --> 00:57:55.560 align:middle line:84%
That proof was based
on the topology

00:57:55.560 --> 00:57:58.190 align:middle line:84%
of R. We'll go through
it, but the topology of R

00:57:58.190 --> 00:57:59.940 align:middle line:84%
and the topology of
Fp are very different.

00:57:59.940 --> 00:58:02.040 align:middle line:90%
And it just doesn't work at all.

00:58:02.040 --> 00:58:06.110 align:middle line:84%
The second reason is that the
statement of the conjecture

00:58:06.110 --> 00:58:08.130 align:middle line:84%
really requires
this to be prime.

00:58:08.130 --> 00:58:10.090 align:middle line:84%
And so it's not
true for any field.

00:58:10.090 --> 00:58:11.768 align:middle line:90%
It's only true for prime fields.

00:58:11.768 --> 00:58:13.310 align:middle line:84%
And so you have to
wonder, how are we

00:58:13.310 --> 00:58:15.750 align:middle line:90%
going to use that in the proof?

00:58:15.750 --> 00:58:19.910 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of methods,
a lot of methods

00:58:19.910 --> 00:58:22.490 align:middle line:84%
don't distinguish between prime
fields and non-prime fields.

00:58:22.490 --> 00:58:24.490 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, they can't
prove the whole thing.

00:58:24.490 --> 00:58:28.590 align:middle line:90%


00:58:28.590 --> 00:58:30.910 align:middle line:84%
In the real analysis
setting, actually, there's

00:58:30.910 --> 00:58:32.270 align:middle line:90%
the same issue.

00:58:32.270 --> 00:58:36.390 align:middle line:84%
So these theorems that I
wasn't able to state precisely

00:58:36.390 --> 00:58:40.010 align:middle line:84%
for you today, they
are true over R2,

00:58:40.010 --> 00:58:44.150 align:middle line:84%
but they are false in C2,
because the complex numbers have

00:58:44.150 --> 00:58:50.870 align:middle line:84%
a subfield R. So the complex
numbers play the role of Fq,

00:58:50.870 --> 00:58:54.070 align:middle line:90%
where q is p squared.

00:58:54.070 --> 00:58:56.790 align:middle line:84%
And so over here, also,
we need to do something

00:58:56.790 --> 00:58:58.750 align:middle line:84%
to distinguish between
the complex numbers

00:58:58.750 --> 00:59:00.950 align:middle line:90%
and the real numbers.

00:59:00.950 --> 00:59:03.550 align:middle line:84%
And many techniques
don't do that.

00:59:03.550 --> 00:59:06.650 align:middle line:90%


00:59:06.650 --> 00:59:10.090 align:middle line:84%
So a bit surprisingly,
these real analysis problems

00:59:10.090 --> 00:59:17.170 align:middle line:84%
that eventually get used in
estimates and Fourier analysis

00:59:17.170 --> 00:59:20.730 align:middle line:84%
with integral operators that
really look like analysis, they

00:59:20.730 --> 00:59:24.290 align:middle line:84%
take something from these
questions over finite fields.

00:59:24.290 --> 00:59:27.570 align:middle line:84%
These are more closely related
to each other than either one

00:59:27.570 --> 00:59:29.760 align:middle line:84%
of them is to that first
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem.

00:59:29.760 --> 00:59:32.875 align:middle line:90%


00:59:32.875 --> 00:59:34.250 align:middle line:84%
So at the beginning
of the class,

00:59:34.250 --> 00:59:37.290 align:middle line:84%
I will teach you some classical
techniques, some double counting

00:59:37.290 --> 00:59:39.790 align:middle line:84%
techniques, some Fourier
analysis techniques.

00:59:39.790 --> 00:59:41.290 align:middle line:90%
Hold on a second.

00:59:41.290 --> 00:59:43.390 align:middle line:84%
And they prove
interesting things.

00:59:43.390 --> 00:59:44.530 align:middle line:90%
And they work over here.

00:59:44.530 --> 00:59:45.970 align:middle line:90%
And they work over here.

00:59:45.970 --> 00:59:48.370 align:middle line:84%
But they don't distinguish
between the prime fields

00:59:48.370 --> 00:59:50.970 align:middle line:90%
and the not-prime fields.

00:59:50.970 --> 00:59:51.470 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:59:51.470 --> 00:59:52.587 align:middle line:90%
Was there a question?

00:59:52.587 --> 00:59:54.170 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does the
fact that the reals

00:59:54.170 --> 00:59:57.310 align:middle line:84%
have the rationals as a subfield
end up mattering for this?

00:59:57.310 --> 01:00:00.516 align:middle line:84%
Or just kind of the topology
argument [INAUDIBLE]?

01:00:00.516 --> 01:00:03.173 align:middle line:90%


01:00:03.173 --> 01:00:04.090 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Ah, OK.

01:00:04.090 --> 01:00:05.910 align:middle line:84%
So the question is--
so the observation

01:00:05.910 --> 01:00:12.310 align:middle line:84%
is, I said that the situation
for Fq, when q is p squared,

01:00:12.310 --> 01:00:17.028 align:middle line:84%
is kind of complicated, because
Fq has a subfield, namely Fp.

01:00:17.028 --> 01:00:19.070 align:middle line:84%
And then I tried to say
there's something similar

01:00:19.070 --> 01:00:21.723 align:middle line:84%
going on with the complex
numbers and the real numbers.

01:00:21.723 --> 01:00:23.390 align:middle line:84%
Now, the observation
is the real numbers

01:00:23.390 --> 01:00:25.710 align:middle line:90%
have many proper subfields.

01:00:25.710 --> 01:00:27.363 align:middle line:84%
One of them is the
rational numbers.

01:00:27.363 --> 01:00:28.780 align:middle line:84%
There are many
more number fields.

01:00:28.780 --> 01:00:31.670 align:middle line:90%


01:00:31.670 --> 01:00:33.950 align:middle line:90%
Doesn't that matter?

01:00:33.950 --> 01:00:36.410 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, that's a good thing
for us to reflect on.

01:00:36.410 --> 01:00:38.870 align:middle line:84%
It turns out not to
matter that much.

01:00:38.870 --> 01:00:42.790 align:middle line:84%
And it's because those
subfields are so small.

01:00:42.790 --> 01:00:45.790 align:middle line:84%
The real numbers are an
infinite order extension

01:00:45.790 --> 01:00:47.310 align:middle line:90%
of the rational numbers.

01:00:47.310 --> 01:00:49.190 align:middle line:84%
I think even an
uncountable order extension

01:00:49.190 --> 01:00:52.750 align:middle line:84%
of the rational
numbers, whereas Fq

01:00:52.750 --> 01:00:54.520 align:middle line:90%
is a degree 2 extension of Fp.

01:00:54.520 --> 01:00:58.730 align:middle line:90%


01:00:58.730 --> 01:01:01.690 align:middle line:84%
So one way people talk
about it is in terms

01:01:01.690 --> 01:01:04.210 align:middle line:90%
of Hausdorff dimension.

01:01:04.210 --> 01:01:08.130 align:middle line:84%
So the real numbers
have subfields,

01:01:08.130 --> 01:01:11.300 align:middle line:84%
but their Hausdorff
dimension is either 0

01:01:11.300 --> 01:01:16.690 align:middle line:84%
or 1 if it's the whole real
numbers and not in the middle.

01:01:16.690 --> 01:01:20.350 align:middle line:90%
Anyway, we'll have a look at it.

01:01:20.350 --> 01:01:20.850 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:01:20.850 --> 01:01:23.017 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do you have any
intuition about why things

01:01:23.017 --> 01:01:24.260 align:middle line:90%
unfold for the small fields?

01:01:24.260 --> 01:01:26.890 align:middle line:90%


01:01:26.890 --> 01:01:30.517 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Why you can't do
something bad with small fields?

01:01:30.517 --> 01:01:32.850 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Yeah, if I understand
the intuition correctly,

01:01:32.850 --> 01:01:35.130 align:middle line:84%
the real numbers are
fine, because they're

01:01:35.130 --> 01:01:38.283 align:middle line:84%
large enough extension
over the rationals.

01:01:38.283 --> 01:01:38.950 align:middle line:90%
So I don't know.

01:01:38.950 --> 01:01:40.170 align:middle line:84%
I'm just wondering
if you have something

01:01:40.170 --> 01:01:41.337 align:middle line:90%
about the size of the space.

01:01:41.337 --> 01:01:51.430 align:middle line:90%


01:01:51.430 --> 01:01:53.650 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So here's
an analogy for you.

01:01:53.650 --> 01:01:55.710 align:middle line:84%
So what if we didn't
have p squared?

01:01:55.710 --> 01:02:00.440 align:middle line:90%
What if we had p to the 17th?

01:02:00.440 --> 01:02:03.840 align:middle line:84%
Now, Fq still has a
subfield Fp, but it's

01:02:03.840 --> 01:02:06.680 align:middle line:90%
kind of a small subfield.

01:02:06.680 --> 01:02:08.700 align:middle line:84%
We could do the
same computation.

01:02:08.700 --> 01:02:12.160 align:middle line:84%
We would see that this
doesn't fully hold,

01:02:12.160 --> 01:02:16.560 align:middle line:84%
but for sets that are
pretty large, for sets

01:02:16.560 --> 01:02:19.720 align:middle line:84%
that are a lot larger than
that, we would still--

01:02:19.720 --> 01:02:22.280 align:middle line:84%
we might still hope
for pretty good bounce.

01:02:22.280 --> 01:02:26.280 align:middle line:84%
And I think that the situation
for the small subfields of R

01:02:26.280 --> 01:02:27.460 align:middle line:90%
is similar to that.

01:02:27.460 --> 01:02:30.983 align:middle line:90%


01:02:30.983 --> 01:02:33.400 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So is this conjecture
known for any prime number

01:02:33.400 --> 01:02:36.800 align:middle line:90%
or is it for every prime?

01:02:36.800 --> 01:02:48.668 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove this
conjecture for R. [INAUDIBLE]

01:02:48.668 --> 01:02:50.460 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So we
stick this tilde here,

01:02:50.460 --> 01:02:52.540 align:middle line:84%
which means there's a
missing constant factor.

01:02:52.540 --> 01:02:53.415 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:02:53.415 --> 01:02:56.700 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: We do
that to be safe, I guess.

01:02:56.700 --> 01:02:59.900 align:middle line:84%
It probably is true with
a small constant factor.

01:02:59.900 --> 01:03:01.860 align:middle line:84%
But strictly speaking,
you can't falsify it

01:03:01.860 --> 01:03:04.040 align:middle line:90%
with one prime number.

01:03:04.040 --> 01:03:06.460 align:middle line:90%
But that's not the real reason.

01:03:06.460 --> 01:03:10.740 align:middle line:84%
Then you might say, if you take
a medium prime number, like 101,

01:03:10.740 --> 01:03:13.180 align:middle line:90%
could you check it numerically?

01:03:13.180 --> 01:03:17.260 align:middle line:84%
Maybe for 100-- even for
101, I don't have any wisdom

01:03:17.260 --> 01:03:18.620 align:middle line:90%
about how to do this.

01:03:18.620 --> 01:03:22.380 align:middle line:84%
And if you literally
did it by brute force

01:03:22.380 --> 01:03:24.320 align:middle line:84%
and checked all the
possibilities x,

01:03:24.320 --> 01:03:27.500 align:middle line:90%
you really couldn't go very far.

01:03:27.500 --> 01:03:30.480 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not sure if
we'll address this,

01:03:30.480 --> 01:03:33.940 align:middle line:84%
but there is a computational
question, like, maybe I

01:03:33.940 --> 01:03:36.480 align:middle line:84%
can't prove this conjecture,
but do I understand it

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:39.900 align:middle line:84%
well enough that I could
prove it for a particular p

01:03:39.900 --> 01:03:43.660 align:middle line:90%
faster than brute force?

01:03:43.660 --> 01:03:44.940 align:middle line:90%
I don't.

01:03:44.940 --> 01:03:47.800 align:middle line:84%
And so we're not able to
have much numerical evidence.

01:03:47.800 --> 01:03:58.353 align:middle line:90%


01:03:58.353 --> 01:04:00.520 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it could be worth
looking for a counterexample

01:04:00.520 --> 01:04:01.187 align:middle line:90%
on the computer.

01:04:01.187 --> 01:04:06.000 align:middle line:84%
The evidence is not that strong
in favor of this conjecture.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:08.280 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:04:08.280 --> 01:04:11.160 align:middle line:84%
In the last 15 minutes, I
wanted to mention to you

01:04:11.160 --> 01:04:13.700 align:middle line:84%
some other parts of math
that this connects to.

01:04:13.700 --> 01:04:19.240 align:middle line:90%


01:04:19.240 --> 01:04:23.000 align:middle line:84%
So one connection is to a part
of combinatorial number theory

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:27.160 align:middle line:84%
called sum product theory, which
we'll see it fits in naturally

01:04:27.160 --> 01:04:27.930 align:middle line:90%
with this issue.

01:04:27.930 --> 01:04:31.800 align:middle line:90%


01:04:31.800 --> 01:04:36.120 align:middle line:84%
So in this example, this
set that we're worried about

01:04:36.120 --> 01:04:39.520 align:middle line:84%
is closely connected
to the fact that Fq

01:04:39.520 --> 01:04:43.440 align:middle line:84%
has a interesting subfield,
an interesting subset that's

01:04:43.440 --> 01:04:46.400 align:middle line:84%
closed under addition
and multiplication.

01:04:46.400 --> 01:04:50.040 align:middle line:84%
And the field-- the sum product
theory and combinatorial number

01:04:50.040 --> 01:04:52.030 align:middle line:84%
theory is about what
happens to a set

01:04:52.030 --> 01:04:54.670 align:middle line:84%
under addition and
multiplication.

01:04:54.670 --> 01:04:57.610 align:middle line:84%
So initially, it's
over R over the reals.

01:04:57.610 --> 01:04:59.040 align:middle line:84%
But then you can
ask in any field.

01:04:59.040 --> 01:05:27.510 align:middle line:90%


01:05:27.510 --> 01:05:30.310 align:middle line:90%
So let's say that R is a ring.

01:05:30.310 --> 01:05:32.750 align:middle line:84%
So we can define
sums and products.

01:05:32.750 --> 01:05:37.510 align:middle line:84%
And A is a subset
of R. So A plus A

01:05:37.510 --> 01:05:40.830 align:middle line:84%
is all of the sums you can
make, two elements of A.

01:05:40.830 --> 01:05:45.550 align:middle line:84%
So it's the set of all the A1
plus A2, where A1 and A2 are

01:05:45.550 --> 01:05:48.790 align:middle line:84%
in A. And the
product set A times

01:05:48.790 --> 01:05:51.360 align:middle line:84%
A is similar to the set
of all the products.

01:05:51.360 --> 01:05:59.050 align:middle line:90%


01:05:59.050 --> 01:06:01.450 align:middle line:84%
So actually, motivating
this from before,

01:06:01.450 --> 01:06:05.810 align:middle line:84%
what was so bad about this
set Fp as a subset of Fq?

01:06:05.810 --> 01:06:13.290 align:middle line:84%
The problem was just that, well,
if these three guys are in Fp,

01:06:13.290 --> 01:06:17.410 align:middle line:84%
then x1 plus t times
x2 is still in Fp.

01:06:17.410 --> 01:06:19.508 align:middle line:84%
So the problem was that
Fp is closed under sums

01:06:19.508 --> 01:06:20.300 align:middle line:90%
and under products.

01:06:20.300 --> 01:06:23.370 align:middle line:90%


01:06:23.370 --> 01:06:25.250 align:middle line:84%
So it raises the
question, are there

01:06:25.250 --> 01:06:28.530 align:middle line:84%
other sets that are maybe not
exactly closed, but roughly

01:06:28.530 --> 01:06:30.040 align:middle line:90%
closed under sums and products?

01:06:30.040 --> 01:06:34.650 align:middle line:90%


01:06:34.650 --> 01:06:41.730 align:middle line:84%
So the idea of sum product
theory is take a subset, A in R.

01:06:41.730 --> 01:06:45.370 align:middle line:84%
Could it happen that both
A plus A and A times A are

01:06:45.370 --> 01:06:45.960 align:middle line:90%
pretty small?

01:06:45.960 --> 01:06:50.710 align:middle line:90%


01:06:50.710 --> 01:06:53.830 align:middle line:84%
So let me mention
a few examples.

01:06:53.830 --> 01:07:00.390 align:middle line:84%
So if A is a subset of the
real numbers, which is generic,

01:07:00.390 --> 01:07:05.110 align:middle line:84%
then A plus A and A
times A would both be

01:07:05.110 --> 01:07:07.390 align:middle line:90%
around the size of A squared.

01:07:07.390 --> 01:07:10.310 align:middle line:84%
So generically, there would
be no coincidences in the sums

01:07:10.310 --> 01:07:12.270 align:middle line:90%
or in the products.

01:07:12.270 --> 01:07:17.830 align:middle line:84%
But it could happen that
A plus A is not very big.

01:07:17.830 --> 01:07:28.550 align:middle line:84%
So if A is an
arithmetic progression,

01:07:28.550 --> 01:07:32.470 align:middle line:84%
then the size of A plus A is
only around 2 times the size

01:07:32.470 --> 01:07:39.030 align:middle line:84%
of A. But in this case, A
times A would be very big.

01:07:39.030 --> 01:07:44.590 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, if A is
a geometric progression,

01:07:44.590 --> 01:07:48.980 align:middle line:84%
then the size of A times A would
be around 2 times the size of A.

01:07:48.980 --> 01:07:51.640 align:middle line:84%
But A is a geometric
progression,

01:07:51.640 --> 01:07:55.080 align:middle line:90%
then A plus A would be very big.

01:07:55.080 --> 01:07:58.620 align:middle line:84%
So based on these few
examples, Erdos and Szemerédi

01:07:58.620 --> 01:08:01.700 align:middle line:84%
conjectured that always
one of these guys is big.

01:08:01.700 --> 01:08:07.900 align:middle line:84%
So here's their conjecture,
as it's still an open problem.

01:08:07.900 --> 01:08:13.020 align:middle line:84%
If A is a finite
subset of the reals,

01:08:13.020 --> 01:08:20.300 align:middle line:84%
then the maximum of A
plus A and A times A

01:08:20.300 --> 01:08:24.760 align:middle line:84%
is at least C epsilon A
to the 2 minus epsilon.

01:08:24.760 --> 01:08:26.380 align:middle line:84%
So for every-- so
at the beginning,

01:08:26.380 --> 01:08:29.180 align:middle line:84%
I should put for every
epsilon bigger than 0.

01:08:29.180 --> 01:08:31.240 align:middle line:90%
So it's not quite a squared.

01:08:31.240 --> 01:08:34.779 align:middle line:84%
That example comes from
taking the numbers 1 to n.

01:08:34.779 --> 01:08:37.580 align:middle line:84%
Then A plus A is
clearly quite small.

01:08:37.580 --> 01:08:43.020 align:middle line:84%
A times A is many of the
integers from 1 to n squared,

01:08:43.020 --> 01:08:44.430 align:middle line:90%
but not all of them.

01:08:44.430 --> 01:08:46.680 align:middle line:84%
Some of them have a prime
factor that's bigger than n.

01:08:46.680 --> 01:08:48.200 align:middle line:90%
So they're not in the list.

01:08:48.200 --> 01:08:50.620 align:middle line:84%
And Erdos computed
that carefully.

01:08:50.620 --> 01:08:52.230 align:middle line:90%
So he said you need the epsilon.

01:08:52.230 --> 01:08:59.359 align:middle line:90%


01:08:59.359 --> 01:09:01.600 align:middle line:84%
So this type of
problem is connected

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:03.479 align:middle line:84%
to progression-- to
projection theory because

01:09:03.479 --> 01:09:04.589 align:middle line:90%
of this type of example.

01:09:04.589 --> 01:09:07.600 align:middle line:90%


01:09:07.600 --> 01:09:10.020 align:middle line:84%
And the connection goes
in both directions.

01:09:10.020 --> 01:09:24.319 align:middle line:90%


01:09:24.319 --> 01:09:31.200 align:middle line:84%
So in one direction,
there's a theorem

01:09:31.200 --> 01:09:34.359 align:middle line:84%
of Elekes about the
sum product theorem.

01:09:34.359 --> 01:09:35.840 align:middle line:90%
So we can't prove this.

01:09:35.840 --> 01:09:39.640 align:middle line:84%
But any exponent here
that's bigger than 1

01:09:39.640 --> 01:09:40.960 align:middle line:90%
would be non-trivial.

01:09:40.960 --> 01:09:42.500 align:middle line:84%
And we can prove
it with exponents

01:09:42.500 --> 01:09:43.819 align:middle line:90%
that are bigger than 1.

01:09:43.819 --> 01:09:47.460 align:middle line:84%
And historically,
there was a big jump

01:09:47.460 --> 01:09:52.500 align:middle line:84%
in the quality of the exponent
when Elekes proved this theorem.

01:09:52.500 --> 01:09:57.620 align:middle line:84%
So he proved that A is a
subset of R, which is finite,

01:09:57.620 --> 01:10:03.180 align:middle line:84%
then the maximum of A plus
A and A times A is at least

01:10:03.180 --> 01:10:03.760 align:middle line:90%
A to the 5/4.

01:10:03.760 --> 01:10:06.820 align:middle line:90%


01:10:06.820 --> 01:10:10.280 align:middle line:84%
And the key ingredient in the
proof was Szemerédi-Trotter.

01:10:10.280 --> 01:10:13.500 align:middle line:90%


01:10:13.500 --> 01:10:18.100 align:middle line:84%
That's not the whole
proof, but the proof uses

01:10:18.100 --> 01:10:20.120 align:middle line:84%
Szemerédi-Trotter,
and not much else.

01:10:20.120 --> 01:10:21.432 align:middle line:90%
It's quite short.

01:10:21.432 --> 01:10:23.640 align:middle line:84%
And so if you know something
about projection theory,

01:10:23.640 --> 01:10:27.460 align:middle line:84%
you can say something
about sum-product theory.

01:10:27.460 --> 01:10:31.780 align:middle line:84%
But later things went
in the other direction.

01:10:31.780 --> 01:10:42.650 align:middle line:84%
So there's a theorem of
Bourgain, Katz, and Tao,

01:10:42.650 --> 01:10:45.370 align:middle line:84%
which says that not only
a prime field does not

01:10:45.370 --> 01:10:47.952 align:middle line:84%
have any subfields,
which we knew,

01:10:47.952 --> 01:10:49.410 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't have
anything that's

01:10:49.410 --> 01:10:52.850 align:middle line:90%
even close to being a subring.

01:10:52.850 --> 01:11:01.970 align:middle line:84%
So if p is prime and A
is a subset of Fp and A

01:11:01.970 --> 01:11:05.450 align:middle line:90%
is not too big.

01:11:05.450 --> 01:11:08.670 align:middle line:84%
So it's not super important
what this number is,

01:11:08.670 --> 01:11:11.560 align:middle line:84%
but A is significantly
smaller than the whole field.

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:15.570 align:middle line:90%


01:11:15.570 --> 01:11:21.890 align:middle line:84%
The maximum of A
plus A and A times A

01:11:21.890 --> 01:11:26.490 align:middle line:84%
is at least the size of
A to the 1 plus epsilon,

01:11:26.490 --> 01:11:28.930 align:middle line:84%
where epsilon is a small,
but explicit number.

01:11:28.930 --> 01:11:30.760 align:middle line:90%
Think something like 1/20.

01:11:30.760 --> 01:11:39.150 align:middle line:90%


01:11:39.150 --> 01:11:41.950 align:middle line:84%
This theorem is actually more
accessible than projection

01:11:41.950 --> 01:11:43.123 align:middle line:90%
theory in general.

01:11:43.123 --> 01:11:44.790 align:middle line:84%
Having these sums and
products gives you

01:11:44.790 --> 01:11:46.170 align:middle line:90%
a little bit more structure.

01:11:46.170 --> 01:11:47.790 align:middle line:90%
It turns out to be important.

01:11:47.790 --> 01:11:51.630 align:middle line:84%
But it shows that
in Fp, over Fp there

01:11:51.630 --> 01:11:54.330 align:middle line:84%
is no example which is too
much like this example.

01:11:54.330 --> 01:11:56.030 align:middle line:84%
You can't just choose
a subset of Fp,

01:11:56.030 --> 01:11:58.412 align:middle line:84%
which is almost closed
under sums and products,

01:11:58.412 --> 01:11:59.620 align:middle line:90%
and then mimic this argument.

01:11:59.620 --> 01:12:02.630 align:middle line:90%


01:12:02.630 --> 01:12:06.550 align:middle line:84%
And it's not
immediate, but this is

01:12:06.550 --> 01:12:19.590 align:middle line:84%
used to improve the projection
theory in Fp squared.

01:12:19.590 --> 01:12:21.390 align:middle line:84%
And something similar
will also happen

01:12:21.390 --> 01:12:23.140 align:middle line:90%
for problems about balls in R2.

01:12:23.140 --> 01:12:41.570 align:middle line:90%


01:12:41.570 --> 01:12:43.550 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to mention
some other applications,

01:12:43.550 --> 01:12:46.510 align:middle line:84%
but I don't want to cram things
in too much in the last 5

01:12:46.510 --> 01:12:47.343 align:middle line:90%
minutes.

01:12:47.343 --> 01:12:49.010 align:middle line:84%
I'll just say a few
words, and then I'll

01:12:49.010 --> 01:12:51.290 align:middle line:90%
pause for final questions.

01:12:51.290 --> 01:12:56.650 align:middle line:84%
So one application or
story is from sieve theory

01:12:56.650 --> 01:12:58.570 align:middle line:90%
in number theory.

01:12:58.570 --> 01:13:00.010 align:middle line:84%
So in sieve theory,
you have a set

01:13:00.010 --> 01:13:04.490 align:middle line:84%
of integers instead of a set
of points in a vector space.

01:13:04.490 --> 01:13:07.490 align:middle line:84%
And in sieve theory,
we study what

01:13:07.490 --> 01:13:09.130 align:middle line:84%
happens if you take
the set of integers

01:13:09.130 --> 01:13:16.090 align:middle line:84%
and you reduce it mod p or mod
q for many different numbers q?

01:13:16.090 --> 01:13:19.250 align:middle line:84%
And there are some questions
about general sets, like,

01:13:19.250 --> 01:13:21.290 align:middle line:84%
could it happen that you
have a set of integers?

01:13:21.290 --> 01:13:24.370 align:middle line:84%
And whenever you reduce
it mod q for any q,

01:13:24.370 --> 01:13:26.730 align:middle line:90%
you always get something small?

01:13:26.730 --> 01:13:30.450 align:middle line:84%
What could you say about
your set of integers?

01:13:30.450 --> 01:13:32.830 align:middle line:84%
So an interesting example of
that are the square numbers.

01:13:32.830 --> 01:13:37.290 align:middle line:84%
If you take the squares and you
reduce it mod p for any prime--

01:13:37.290 --> 01:13:38.370 align:middle line:90%
you start with primes--

01:13:38.370 --> 01:13:40.670 align:middle line:84%
you get the quadratic
residues, which is only half

01:13:40.670 --> 01:13:42.710 align:middle line:90%
of the residue classes.

01:13:42.710 --> 01:13:44.470 align:middle line:84%
So whenever you reduce
it mod p, you only

01:13:44.470 --> 01:13:46.710 align:middle line:90%
get half of the residue classes.

01:13:46.710 --> 01:13:48.470 align:middle line:84%
How many other sets
of integers can you

01:13:48.470 --> 01:13:51.290 align:middle line:84%
think of that whenever
you reduce the mod p,

01:13:51.290 --> 01:13:54.950 align:middle line:84%
you only get half of
the residue classes?

01:13:54.950 --> 01:13:57.990 align:middle line:84%
How big could such a
set of integers be?

01:13:57.990 --> 01:13:59.450 align:middle line:84%
What fraction of
all the integers?

01:13:59.450 --> 01:14:00.830 align:middle line:90%
And so on.

01:14:00.830 --> 01:14:03.450 align:middle line:84%
So there's one set of
questions about this.

01:14:03.450 --> 01:14:04.950 align:middle line:84%
And there's another
set of questions

01:14:04.950 --> 01:14:06.790 align:middle line:84%
where you take a
particular set of integers

01:14:06.790 --> 01:14:09.290 align:middle line:84%
that you might be interested
in, of which the most famous is

01:14:09.290 --> 01:14:10.110 align:middle line:90%
the primes.

01:14:10.110 --> 01:14:11.652 align:middle line:84%
And you think about
what happens when

01:14:11.652 --> 01:14:16.910 align:middle line:84%
you reduce the set the primes
mod q for many different q.

01:14:16.910 --> 01:14:20.470 align:middle line:84%
So it appears to be the case
that the prime numbers are

01:14:20.470 --> 01:14:25.990 align:middle line:84%
evenly distributed
mod q for every q.

01:14:25.990 --> 01:14:29.910 align:middle line:84%
Actually, depending on how you
quantify it, that's a theorem.

01:14:29.910 --> 01:14:33.300 align:middle line:84%
So if you fix a q and you
take the primes mod q,

01:14:33.300 --> 01:14:35.640 align:middle line:84%
and you take primes up to
x, where x is much, much,

01:14:35.640 --> 01:14:37.300 align:middle line:90%
much bigger than q.

01:14:37.300 --> 01:14:40.740 align:middle line:84%
They will be evenly distributed
among the residue classes mod

01:14:40.740 --> 01:14:42.380 align:middle line:84%
q that are possible,
the ones that

01:14:42.380 --> 01:14:45.684 align:middle line:90%
have no common factor with q.

01:14:45.684 --> 01:14:47.740 align:middle line:84%
But you could have--
you might also

01:14:47.740 --> 01:14:51.060 align:middle line:84%
want to know if you take the
primes up to some fixed x

01:14:51.060 --> 01:14:54.935 align:middle line:84%
and you reduce them mod
q for many different q,

01:14:54.935 --> 01:14:57.060 align:middle line:84%
it still appears-- it
appears that those are evenly

01:14:57.060 --> 01:15:01.180 align:middle line:84%
distributed for quite big
q, even q's that are only

01:15:01.180 --> 01:15:03.000 align:middle line:90%
slightly less than x.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:06.800 align:middle line:90%


01:15:06.800 --> 01:15:09.620 align:middle line:84%
We can't prove
anything like that.

01:15:09.620 --> 01:15:12.860 align:middle line:84%
But there's a line of
thought that maybe we

01:15:12.860 --> 01:15:15.200 align:middle line:84%
could relax what we're
trying to prove a little bit.

01:15:15.200 --> 01:15:17.160 align:middle line:84%
And instead of trying
to prove it for every q,

01:15:17.160 --> 01:15:21.340 align:middle line:84%
we could try to prove
it for most of the q.

01:15:21.340 --> 01:15:26.522 align:middle line:84%
Now we're in this setting
where we have one fixed set,

01:15:26.522 --> 01:15:27.980 align:middle line:84%
and we're looking
at how it reduces

01:15:27.980 --> 01:15:30.600 align:middle line:90%
mod q for many different q.

01:15:30.600 --> 01:15:33.680 align:middle line:84%
And that problem is very
similar to the projection theory

01:15:33.680 --> 01:15:35.960 align:middle line:90%
problem.

01:15:35.960 --> 01:15:39.480 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so we'll teach some
core techniques of projection

01:15:39.480 --> 01:15:41.960 align:middle line:84%
theory that were developed by
people in geometric measure

01:15:41.960 --> 01:15:44.320 align:middle line:84%
theory in the '60s,
'70s, and '80s.

01:15:44.320 --> 01:15:46.280 align:middle line:90%
And those are almost--

01:15:46.280 --> 01:15:48.920 align:middle line:84%
those are very closely parallel
to the classic techniques

01:15:48.920 --> 01:15:51.480 align:middle line:84%
of sieve theory that
were developed by people

01:15:51.480 --> 01:15:53.080 align:middle line:90%
in the '40s, '50s, '60s.

01:15:53.080 --> 01:15:56.900 align:middle line:90%


01:15:56.900 --> 01:15:58.680 align:middle line:84%
So interesting
connections there.

01:15:58.680 --> 01:16:03.400 align:middle line:84%
In sieve theory, there
are lots of open problems.

01:16:03.400 --> 01:16:06.280 align:middle line:84%
So that's one set of
applications, if you like,

01:16:06.280 --> 01:16:07.300 align:middle line:90%
or connections.

01:16:07.300 --> 01:16:10.840 align:middle line:90%


01:16:10.840 --> 01:16:15.040 align:middle line:84%
And the other one I wanted to
mention is dynamical systems.

01:16:15.040 --> 01:16:18.560 align:middle line:84%
So Elon Lindenstrauss last
year gave the Simons lectures.

01:16:18.560 --> 01:16:21.440 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things
was about taking orbits

01:16:21.440 --> 01:16:23.573 align:middle line:84%
in homogeneous
spaces, unipotent--

01:16:23.573 --> 01:16:25.740 align:middle line:84%
so I don't have time to say
what all the things are.

01:16:25.740 --> 01:16:29.000 align:middle line:84%
But you take unipotent
orbits in homogeneous spaces,

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:30.410 align:middle line:84%
then they distribute
very evenly.

01:16:30.410 --> 01:16:34.060 align:middle line:90%


01:16:34.060 --> 01:16:38.460 align:middle line:84%
So there are some classical
important theorems about that.

01:16:38.460 --> 01:16:41.540 align:middle line:84%
And the recent thing
he and Amir Mohammadi

01:16:41.540 --> 01:16:43.340 align:middle line:84%
were trying to make
it more quantitative.

01:16:43.340 --> 01:16:44.882 align:middle line:84%
And a new idea in
their proof is they

01:16:44.882 --> 01:16:47.100 align:middle line:90%
brought in projection theory.

01:16:47.100 --> 01:16:50.320 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so I will tell
you the story, slowly.

01:16:50.320 --> 01:16:52.140 align:middle line:84%
First of all, what
is the question?

01:16:52.140 --> 01:16:55.780 align:middle line:84%
And then, what does it have
to do with projection theory?

01:16:55.780 --> 01:16:59.940 align:middle line:84%
So those are some applications
I was thinking that I'd

01:16:59.940 --> 01:17:01.800 align:middle line:90%
like to talk about with you.

01:17:01.800 --> 01:17:05.180 align:middle line:90%


01:17:05.180 --> 01:17:06.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:06.540 --> 01:17:09.440 align:middle line:90%
Any last questions or comments?

01:17:09.440 --> 01:17:09.940 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:17:09.940 --> 01:17:10.580 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering if you'll

01:17:10.580 --> 01:17:12.300 align:middle line:90%
tell us about the [INAUDIBLE]?

01:17:12.300 --> 01:17:26.030 align:middle line:90%


01:17:26.030 --> 01:17:28.530 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So the question
is that the Szemerédi-Trotter

01:17:28.530 --> 01:17:30.430 align:middle line:84%
theorem is usually set
in a different way,

01:17:30.430 --> 01:17:33.030 align:middle line:84%
actually a more general way,
where you have a set of lines.

01:17:33.030 --> 01:17:34.530 align:middle line:84%
And you look at the
points that have

01:17:34.530 --> 01:17:36.890 align:middle line:90%
many lines going through them.

01:17:36.890 --> 01:17:39.770 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see that this is
a corollary or special case

01:17:39.770 --> 01:17:42.650 align:middle line:90%
of that.

01:17:42.650 --> 01:17:46.970 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: That's like the
version of this [INAUDIBLE]

01:17:46.970 --> 01:17:51.690 align:middle line:90%
problem in Fp.

01:17:51.690 --> 01:17:54.970 align:middle line:90%
They are quite different.

01:17:54.970 --> 01:17:59.730 align:middle line:84%
For example, if
you just estimate

01:17:59.730 --> 01:18:06.290 align:middle line:84%
the number of average points, we
know that the bulk in our tree

01:18:06.290 --> 01:18:09.697 align:middle line:90%
does not hold.

01:18:09.697 --> 01:18:10.530 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:18:10.530 --> 01:18:12.490 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about
that after class.

01:18:12.490 --> 01:18:13.270 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:18:13.270 --> 01:18:14.430 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK, good.

01:18:14.430 --> 01:18:16.570 align:middle line:90%
Let's stop there for today.

01:18:16.570 --> 01:18:18.960 align:middle line:90%
I will see you on Thursday.

01:18:18.960 --> 01:18:25.000 align:middle line:90%